<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Preparations In Place In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The preparations for Zimbabwe's
presidential elections, scheduled to be held this weekend, are
in place, a poll official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Election Directorate Chairman Mariyawanda Nzuwah said about
3.3 million U.S. dollars had been spent to set up some 3,049
polling centers for the presidential election, the second since
the country's independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Nzuwah said over 4.9 million registered voters of the
country's 10.5 million population are expected to go to the
polls, slightly more than those for last year's parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
Registrar-General Tobaiwa Mudede said the counting would begin
on Monday at 7:00 a.m. at all the counting centers in the
country.
</P>
<P>
And it was hoped that results would be ready the same day,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Current President Robert Mugabe is now only being challenged
by the opposition United Parties President retired bishop Abel
Muzorewa.
</P>
<P>
Answering whether Muzorewa will withdraw from the race, Mudede
said he had not received any notice of withdrawal from Mozorewa.
</P>
<P>
"If Muzorewa decides to pull out it would be very unfortunate
as everything is now in place. The ballot papers are already in
the hands of polling officers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reports say if Muzorewa withdraws from the race, the
government will lose about 4.4 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
