<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Urges For Protection of Revived EAC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
ARUSHA (TANZANIA), March 14 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Salim Ahmed Salim,
the Secretary General of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
today urged Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania to protect their newly
established East African Co-operation (EAC).
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief made the appeal at the historical re-launching
of the EAC at the Sheikh Amri Abeid Stadium in Arusha, Northern
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The revival of the cooperation among the three sister
countries should be maintained for the benefits of the people of
the three devoloping countries, according to the OAU chief.
</P>
<P>
"African continent will only survive through total
co-operation among their states," said Dr. Salim before Kenyan
President Daniel Moi, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
He assured the three leaders that OAU was highly impressed by
the success in reviving their co-operation in economic, political
and social aspects.
</P>
<P>
He urged the three presidents to ensure that all set goals
under the new co-opertion would be fully implemented by their
governments.
</P>
<P>
While commending Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania for their
revolutionary ideas, Dr. Salim warned them not to forget the
weakness which led to the collapse of the former East African
Community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
