<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Clashes in Bangladesh Opposition's Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Sporadic incidents involving bomb
blasts and clashes marked the sixth day of the opposition's
non-cooperation campaign in the capital today, leaving about 15
people injured.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the official BSS news agency, six
people were admitted to hospital with bomb injuries, and two of
them were in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
Five people were also injured when a bomb exploded inside a
temple while four others were hurt in clashes between rival
political activists, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The mainstream opposition parties led by the Awami (People's)
League began their non-cooperation campaign last Saturday in a bid
to annul the ruling Bangladesh Nationalist Party-held February 15
elections and force the resignation of the present "illegal"
government to pave the way for fresh elections under a neutral
caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that despite some incidents of clashes,
reports of violence were fewer today than the previous days, and
no one was arrested.
</P>
<P>
Banks and other financial institutions as well as a large
number of shops and other businesses opened today, although
automobiles remained off the road and train services were
disrupted due to blockades installed at different points.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the opposition parties had announced partial
relaxations of their campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
