<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Zimbabwean Offenders Serve Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Over 4,000 offenders did
community service in Zimbabwe last year, indicating a 50 percent
increase over the previous year, community service national
coordinator Andrew Musengezi said today.
</P>
<P>
Musengezi expected a further increase in the service as
magistrates began to appreciate its importance.
</P>
<P>
He said the first two months of this year had already seen
1,000 people doing community service.
</P>
<P>
"In 1993 we had 682 cases and this rose to 2,494 in 1994 and
last year we had 4,578 cases. This shows that it is gaining
ground and even our default rate is around five percent," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Community service was introduced in 1993 with the aim of
reducing prison congestion and rehabilitating offenders.
</P>
<P>
He noted the introduction of community service had seen the
stablization of the prison population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
