<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross Resumes Touch With Kidnappers Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), working as a
mediator in efforts for the release of the hostages held by the
Free Papua Movement (OPM) since January 8, have resumed contact
with the OPM.
</P>
<P>
Contact with the OPM was cut off several days ago, but was
resumed Wednesday evening with OPM leaders Daniel Yudas Kogoya and
Kelly kwalik, who are based in Irian Jaya, according to an Antara
news agency report from Jayapura, capital of the region.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC team, which has just returned from negotiations with
senior OPM leader Mozes Weror in neighboring Papua New Guinea,
flew to the OPM hiding place at border areas in Jayawijaya and
Paniai districts.
</P>
<P>
There are no hints yet as to whether the hostages will be
released soon by their captors.
</P>
<P>
The OPM on January 8 kidnapped 26 people including seven
foreigners who were on a scientific expedition in the deep areas
of Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
Later, the OPM released 14 hostages including a German. The
remaining 12, including four Britons and two Dutch nationals, are
still in the hands of the OPM.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian military is now trying to gain the safe release
of the hostages. However, it has warned that the hostage issue
cannot be dragged on for too long and that it will consider
military options if necessary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
