<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain in Grief After Scottish School Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain has been overcome today by
grief brought about by the killing in a primary school in the town
of Dunblane, Perthshire, central Scotland, Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
A gunman armed with four semi-automatic pistols burst into the
school gym and opened fire at 29 children aged four to six.
Sixteen pupils and their woman teacher were killed and another 12
children wounded. Then the gunman killed himself.
</P>
<P>
The British parliament is in a sombre mood today, united in its
horror and condemnation of the barbarous killing.
</P>
<P>
It was announced that Queen Elizabeth II and her daughter
Princess Royal Anne are to visit Dunblance next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The queen sent messages of condolence Wednesday to the victims
of the massacre and their families, expressing her "deepest and
most heartfelt sympathy."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Major told the House of Commons that it was
an event of "almost unimaginable horror" and that many questions
would have to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government would consider the implications of
the massacre when considering future firearms legislation.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister is to visit the town of Dunblane Friday in a
non-political role as a representative of the whole of the House
of Commons.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth, who flew to the
scene, announced in the house an inquiry into the murderous event.
</P>
<P>
Forsyth told the House of Commons that senior Scottish judge
Lord Cullen had agreed to carry out the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
He said he had witnessed the scene which "encompassed both the
worst and the best of which humanity is capable."
</P>
<P>
Opposition Labor leader Tony Blair expressed his grief
sentiments by saying, "Politics is silent today. We grieve. We
stand in solidarity with the community of Dunblane."
</P>
<P>
It was reported eight children and two teachers injured in the
massacre remain in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Five of the children are in intensive care and one is said to
be in critical condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
