<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EAC Secretariat Inaugurated In Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
ARUSHA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Secretariat of the East
African Co-operation (EAC) is today inaugurated by the heads of
state of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Marking the historical event at the Sheikh Amri Abeid Stadium
in Arusha, Northern Tanzania, were Kenyan President Daniel Arap
moi, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Other dignitaries attending the inauguration ceremony included
Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu, Organization Of African
Unity (OAU) chief Salim Ahmed Salim and former Tanzanian
presidents Julius Nyerere and Ali Hassan Mwinyi.
</P>
<P>
In a warm and cordial atmosphere, the three East African
leaders appointed Kenyan Ambassodar Francis Kirimi Muthaura the
Executive Secretary of the EAC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
In their inauguration speeches, the three East African leaders
described the day as a historical one producing results of common
desire.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have begun to pay off since the three countries
started to seek the replacement of the defunct East African
Community by the currently inaugurated East African Co-operation,
according to the three leaders.
</P>
<P>
The presidents also commended the retired president Mwalimu
Nyerere for his recent effort to bring peace in Burundi and help
Burundians enter into dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Moi, who is the Chairman of the summit,
stressed the point that Africa would be built by Africans
themselves.
</P>
<P>
"Let us work together, build East Africa that is stronger than
before," he appealed in the Kiswahili language.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Museveni underscored the need to improve
roads on the borders of the three countries in order to enhance
trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Besiness needs fast travelling, going out and coming back
home," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian President Mkapa expressed thanks to the fore-leaders
of East Africa, especially Mwalimu Nyerere, who was one of the
founders of the defunct East African Community.
</P>
<P>
"They had a great vision, and we are just following their
way," Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
In his message of congratulation, OAU chief Salim Ahmed Salim
noted that one of the lessons to be learnt from the death of the
East African Community was that co-operation was vital for the
development of Africa and the people.
</P>
<P>
According to a communigue signed by the three presidents at
the ceremony, areas of co-opearation under the newly established
EAC involve transport and communication, trade, industry,
agriculture and education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
