<HEADLINE> Jobless Rate Among UK Ethnic Minorities Remains High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain's ethnic minorities have
not benefited as much as the white population from the improvement
in the labor market in the past year, the Central Statistical
Office's latest quarterly labor force survey showed.
</P>
<P>
In the year to autumn 1995, the unemployment rate among whites
fell from 8.5 percent to 8 percent, while that for ethnic
minorities fell from 19.1 to 18.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
This is relatively unusual in that unemployment and employment
among ethnic minorities are normally "supercyclical." Unemployment
is higher on average for minorities than whites, but tends to fall
faster in good times and rise more quickly in bad times.
</P>
<P>
Women from minorities have done particularly badly. Their
unemployment rate rose by 1.5 percentage points in the year to
autumn 1995, while unemployment rates decline for white men and
women and men from minorities.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rates vary widely between different minorities.
Last autumn the worst affected were Pakistanis and Bangladeshis,
with a jobless rate of 28.7 percent, followed by people of African
and Caribbean origin, with a jobless rate of 22.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
