<HEADLINE> Nepal's Ruling Partner Not to Support No-Confidence  Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The National Democratic Party
(RPP), Nepal's third largest party and the ruling partner in the
present coalition government, would not support a no- confidence
motion against the government, it leader said today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to President of the main opposition Communist Party
of Nepal (UML) Man Mohan Adhikari, RPP President Surya Bahadur
Thapa said his party could not cooperation with the opposition on
this matter.
</P>
<P>
The opposition would table a no-confidence motion against the
three-party government under Nepali Congress (NC) Party leader
Sher Bahadur Deuba in parliament next week.
</P>
<P>
It would be immoral for a responsible party to throw its weight
behind a no-confidence motion against its own government, he said.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of his party, Thapa said in the letter that his
party's decision is to remain in the coalition government with the
NC and the Goodwill Party.
</P>
<P>
However, rumors had it that the RPP might split in the coming
days as party leaders differ over whether the party should support
the UML-sponsored no-confidence motion during a special session of
the House of Representatives beginning on March 20.
</P>
<P>
The RPP, which has 19 seats in the 205-member House of
Representatives, holds the balance for the survival of the present
coalition government. The UML and the main ruling NC party hold
88 and 86 seats respectively.
</P>
<P>
The UML has offered to form an alternative coalition government
led by the RPP if the RPP supports its motion to topple down the
present NC-led government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
