<HEADLINE> Delinquent Credit Card Loans Hit 10-Year High in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Delinquent credit card loans
in the U.S. hit a 10-year high in the fourth quarter of 1995, a
survey by the American Bankers Association (ABA) said today.
</P>
<P>
Credit card accounts that were 30 days or more overdue rose to
3.34 percent in the quarter, up from 3.30 percent in the previous
quarter and 2.93 percent in 1994. The fourth quarter levels
matched the previous high of 3.34 percent in the first quarter of
1991.
</P>
<P>
The amount of dollars owed on the delinquent credit card
accounts rose to 4.45 percent, up from 3.20 percent in 1994, the
ABA said.
</P>
<P>
ABA economist James Chessen said the increases in late payments
have slowed, but "the level of delinquencies is still alarming."
</P>
<P>
Economists blame the rising delinquencies on a variety of
factors, including stagnant paychecks, banks' mass marketing of
credit cards and consumer spending habits that disregard rising
personal debt.
</P>
<P>
The ABA survey also found rising delinquencies in closed-end
consumer installment loans, or loans with a specific payment date,
which crept up to 2.12 percent or 0.14 percentage points higher
than the third quarter of 1995. Delinquencies for direct auto
loans rose to 1.87 percent, up 0.22 percentage points from the
third quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
