<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Couple Accused of Embezzling Through Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A Greek couple has been accused
of embezzling an unknown sum of money through computer, said local
press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The husband-and-wife team, whose names have not been disclosed,
were employed at the Finance Ministry's computing center and a
tax office respectively. The incident is believed to be one of
Greece's first ever white-collar computer crimes.
</P>
<P>
As a computer systems analyst and programmer, he regularly
broke into computer archives, in collaboration with his wife, a
cashier at a district tax office, to slash off zeroes. After
understating the amounts of actual taxes and fines paid by
taxpayers at the tax office, they would then forge receipts with
the reduced amount to pocket the difference.
</P>
<P>
The scan was confirmed Wednesday by the country's Deputy
Finance Minister George Anomeritis who said this was an isolated
case and the ministry's computers were essentially safe from
hackers.
</P>
<P>
So far, it is not known the couple were working solely for
themselves or on behalf of others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
