<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Wholesale Prices Down 0.2 Pct in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. wholesale prices fell 0.2
percent in February, the first decline in eight months, according
to a report by the Labor Department today.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department said the drop in its Producer Price
Index (PPI) was the first since an identical decline last June and
it resulted mainly from a milder weather which restrained the
energy prices.
</P>
<P>
Energy costs dropped 0.7 percent after shooting up 2.9 percent
in January and 3.7 percent in December. It was the first drop
since energy prices fell 1 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
Food prices also declined in February for the second straight
month, down 0.3 percent after a 0.2 percent fall a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile food and energy components, the core
index rose a slight 0.1 percent. Overall, wholesale prices were
rising at a 0.9 percent annual rate during the first two months of
1996.
</P>
<P>
The PPI measures cost pressures before they reach the consumer.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government reported last week that 705,000 new jobs
were created in February, pushing the jobless rate down to 5.5
percent from 5.8 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
And the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) reported Wednesday that a
nationwide survey showed the economy was growing modestly in
January and February. At the same time, the survey found subdued
wage and price pressures.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the employment figure and the Fed's report
on the U.S. economy may dim the hope that the Federal Open Market
Committee will cut the interest rate when it meets on March 26
despite the lower inflation rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
