<HEADLINE> Russia to Launch Another Military Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Military Space Forces
will launch a military satellite from the Plesetsk Space Center
today, on the eve of the space center's 30th anniversary, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be put into orbit by a Soyuz-U rocket which
is scheduled to blast off at 20:40 Moscow time (17:40 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The Soviet Union's first military satellite, a Kosmos-112, was
launched from Plesetsk in the northern Arkhangelsk region on March
17, 1966.
</P>
<P>
Since then, 62 percent of Russia's satellites and 40 percent of
the world's satellites have been launched from Plesetsk. The
satellite to be launched today will be the 1862nd satellite
lifting off from the site.
</P>
<P>
The space center had its highest launch rate in 1977, when 70
booster rockets placed 76 satellites in orbit. Plesetsk launch
programs employ boosters of the Soyuz, Molniya, Tsiklon and Kosmos
series to deploy communications, survey, navigation and weather
satellites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
