<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Closes Office in Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees today announced the closure of its
office in Santiago, Chile, on this very day after 22 years of
service to refugees and returnees in the South American country.
</P>
<P>
The move came as a result of the democratic reforms and other
positive and fundamental changes in the Chilean society, which
makes the need for asylum no longer exist, according to the UNHCR
in a press release issued today.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the office began its work in Chile in
1973, a week after the overthrow of the government of Salvador
Allende and has since helped thousands of foreign refugees to seek
a second country of asylum.
</P>
<P>
During 1973 and 1974, the office managed to find resettlement
for about 2,600 foreign refugees, who either returned to their
home countries or remained in Chile.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, more than 200,000 Chileans were also
provided with protection and legal assistance by UNHCR offices in
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR said that Chile's democratic reforms beginning 1988
boosted the return of refugees to the country. In 1990, an
official request for UNHCR help in promoting voluntary
repatriation was put forward by the Chilean government. In early
1994, the UNHCR declared the Cessation Clause applicable to
Chilean refugees.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR added that its Regional Office in Buenos Aires will
now be in charge of promoting refugee legislation and dealing with
individual cases in Chile.
</P>
<P>
A closure ceremony was held today at Chile's Presidential
Palace. Attending the ceremony was Assistant High Commissioner
Sergio Vieira de Mello, representing U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees Sadako Ogata. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
