<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief Executives of Romanian Bank Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Romania's Central Bank has
removed from office 12 senior executives of the Dacia Felix Bank,
including the president and the governor, accusing them of
violating credit and foreign exchange regulations.
</P>
<P>
Dacia Felix, a joint venture bank, granted credits without
guarantees, resulting in large losses of funds. The bank's
supervisor Sever Muresan fled the country with 500 million
U.S. dollars recently.
</P>
<P>
The removal of the Dacia Felix executives has shocked Romanian
financial circles. Worried depositors withdrew around 1.6 billion
leus (560,000 U.S. dollars) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vasile Dumitru has been appointed the new governor of Dacia
Felix, which is based in the city of Cluj-Napoca in northwestern
Romania.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Central Bank, there are 23 commercial banks and 12
joint venture and foreign banks in the East European country.
</P>
<P>
The last serious financial crime occurred in January 1995 when
the then-President of the Credit Bank, Ivan Marcel, was arrested
on charges of bribery and forgery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
