<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Concludes Solidarity Visit to Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
left Israel for Washington this evening, concluding his 22-hour
solidarity visit to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres and some other Israeli
officials were at the Ben-Gurion Airport to see him off.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived here Wednesday night from Sharm el-Sheikh,
Egypt after attending the anti-terror summit in the aftermath of
the recent Hamas suicide attacks in Israel which killed 58
people. This is his third visit to Israel as U.S. President.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Clinton reiterated U.S. support for Israel in
the war against terrorism and for the continuation of the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Clinton met with Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres and other Israeli officials to discuss the issue of
anti-Israeli attacks by Islamic extremists.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference along with Peres, Clinton announced that
the U.S. will commit more than 100 million U.S. dollars to assist
Israel in combating terror.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton said the two countries will immediately try
to conclude a bilateral agreement on combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He said that under the agreement, the U.S. will immediately
begin to provide Israel with additional equipment and training.
</P>
<P>
Both sides will join together to develop new anti-terror
methods and technologies. And both countries will work to enhance
communications and coordination in the war against terror.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who accompanied
Clinton on the visit, will remain here to finalize details of the
document.
</P>
<P>
Later, Clinton laid a wreath before the grave of late Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who was assassinated on November 4,
1995.
</P>
<P>
Also this morning, the U.S. President held talks with Israeli
opposition leader Binyamin Netanyahu and Jerusalem Mayor Ehud
Olmert.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving the country, Clinton gave a speech to the
Israeli people at the Tel Aviv Center for Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
He said that Wednesday's meeting in the Egyptian Red Sea resort
of Sharm el-Sheikh showed that Israel is not alone in this region
because leaders of 13 Arab countries attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that peace and security is inseparable. "Fear (of
terror) must be conquered, security must be achieved and peace
must be pursued," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We know that Israel will never let her enemies achieve the
victory they seek and will never abandon the hope of peace," said
Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
