<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Optimistic About Pakistan's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior World Bank Official
today expressed her optimism over higher economic growth in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Economic reports suggest that the prospects for higher economic
growth and lower inflation for the current fiscal year had been
improved, said Nieko Nishimizu, the Country Director of the World
Bank's South Asia Regional Office.
</P>
<P>
Nishimizu, who is about to complete a three-week visit to
Pakistan, said in a statement to the press that the stabilization
of the economy and improved conditions had now laid the basis for
meeting the long-term development challenges facing the country.
</P>
<P>
She noted that Pakistan's economic performance has responded
favorably to the government's timely and effective short-term
stabilization measures.
</P>
<P>
"My optimism is based on the favorable response by the economy
to the government's stabilization measures in recent months and I
believe that not many developing countries could have such a quick
response," she said.
</P>
<P>
Nishimizu urged Pakistan to broaden and deepen structural
policy reforms and institutional development to realize its full
growth and employment potential.
</P>
<P>
Observing that as a result of the government's Social Action
Program (SAP), progress is being made in delivery of basic social
services, she promised that the World Bank would continue to give
top priority to the SAP.
</P>
<P>
She emphasized the importance of a strong partnership between
the government, communities and Non-Governmental Organizations
(NGOS) in delivering quality social services in a cost-effective
manner.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in Pakistan, Nishimizu visited rural areas in
the Provinces of Balochistan, Northwest Frontier, Punjab and Sindh
and the Northern Areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
