<HEADLINE> Greek FM invites FYROM Counterpart to Visit Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos has invited his former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia
(FYROM) counterpart Ljubomir Frckovski to visit Athens for talks
on bilateral issues, government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said
today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman clarified however that the talks would not touch
on the issue of the neighboring state's name, regarding which
months-long negotiations have been going on in New York between
representatives of the two countries under the aegis of U.N.
mediator Cyrus Vance.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said that the two foreign ministers would discuss
economic and trade relations between Athens and Skopje. The date
for the meeting would be set after the reply to the invitation has
been received, he added.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek Prime Minister Kostas Simitis
had separate talks today on the FYROM name issue with the
country's opposition party leaders with the aim "to create a
broad front on a common basis on the issue."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after the talks, Simitis said that
Greece's relations with the FYROM were developing and "the ice is
melting." Economic and trade cooperation between the two countries
was developing "very positively" and only the problem of the name
remained, he said. 
</P>
