<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killer Drug Should Be Dealt With Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Sports chiefs should quicken their
pace to develop a new scientific way to remove the use of the
fatal, blood-doping drug erythropoietin (EPO), a leading doping
expert said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have been studying hard in the field and those from
Canada, France and the United States said on Thursday that they
had found a possible way of detecting the drug.
</P>
<P>
The tests can be carried out on both blood and urine but the
introduction of blood testing would certainly help improve the new
technique.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee, which presently conducts
urine tests, has decided against introducing blood testing at this
year's Olympics.
</P>
<P>
By increasing the red blood cells which transport oxygen
around the body, EPO is perfect for athletes who want to cheat in
endurance events like cycling, rowing and distance running.
</P>
<P>
But it is suspected that at least 18 riders in Europe have
died after taking the drug since it was first developed in the
mid-1980s to treat kidney disease.
</P>
<P>
The substance is produced naturally in the body. But
scientists said artificial EPO can be fatal, leading to high blood
pressure, a thrombosis or a heart attack and also breaking down
the entire circulatory system.
</P>
<P>
The use of EPO was banned by the IOC in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Launches New EAC In Arusha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
today appealed to East African countries not to repeat the
mistake that led to the collapse of the East African Community
(EAC) in 1977.
</P>
<P>
President Moi pointed out that the launching of the East
African Co-operation 19 years after the EAC collapse is a great
hope for a better future of East Africa.
</P>
<P>
President Moi was speaking from the Sheik Hamri Abeid Stadium
in Arusha, northern Tanzania, where he presided over the East
African Co-operation Summit and the inauguration of its
secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Together with Moi at the summit were his counterparts Benjamin
Mkapa of Tanzania and Yoweri Museveni of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan president said on the occasion that by launching
the co-operation, the three leaders have set the stage for their
peoples to benefit from the renewed spirit of East African unity.
</P>
<P>
Thus, he said, there is need to address critical issues such
as modalities for a harmonized monetary policy and the free
movement of people across national borders.
</P>
<P>
There is also need to consider the benefits to be derived from
common tariffs and the harmonization of customs services, he
added.
</P>
<P>
However, the region of the East Africa must not lose sight of
obstacles that can jeopardize the collective progress, he warned.
</P>
<P>
President Moi listed the serious economic problems in the face
of East Africa as heavy debt burden, poor commodity prices and
threat to their infant industries.
</P>
<P>
Apart from this, the three East African countries are being
challenged by the emerging regional groupings such as the
European Union, according to the president.
</P>
<P>
Such groupings are imposing trading conditions that restrict
the entry of goods from East Africa to their markets, he said,
adding that the East African countries need to enhance their
joint bargaining power in order to ensure their economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Other dignitaries present at the summit include former
Tanzanian presidents Julius Nyerere and Hassan Ali Mwinyi,
Rwandese President Pasteaur Bizimungu and the Secretary General
of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU), Dr Salim Ahamed
Salim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
