<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Court Tells Press to be Discreet on Hawala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- India's Supreme Court has asked
the media to exercise restraint when reporting proceedings in the
hawala bribery case, the Hindustan times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The hawala case is an 18-million-U.S.-dollar bribery scandal
which involves more than 20 leading politicians in the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is the function and right of the media to gather and convey
information to the public about the case without violating the
presumption of innocence," said a three-judge bench during the
resumed hearing of the case yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The presiding judge, J.S. Verma, said "The media have an
obligation to report faithfully ... otherwise the reporting of the
case would become detrimental to public interest."
</P>
<P>
He said he was extremely disturbed at the kind of publicity
given to the hawala case.
</P>
<P>
"This case was like any other case for the court," Justice
Verma said. But media reports gave an impression as if he was
taking an unusual interest, he said, adding that this had
disturbed and embarrassed him.
</P>
<P>
Justice Verma, who recently gave an interview to a news
magazine, was reportedly annoyed by the report which portrayed him
as the hero judge in the hawala case.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
