<HEADLINE> Major Pledges to Get Tough on Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
said today that his government will do all it can to stop foreign
terrorist groups from getting foothold in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told BBC Radio that he would introduce new
anti-terrorism legislation if necessary.
</P>
<P>
He pledged "any information on terrorism fund-raising, or other
support, will be carefully examined."
</P>
<P>
He said that it was time to look at those who used safe havens
abroad "to foster dissent elsewhere" to create a climate in which
terrorism could flourish.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the British government will open a debate
in parliament on the renewal of the Prevention of Terrorism Act.
</P>
<P>
It seems that the renewal of the act has been considered
natural after the Irish Republican Army plotted the huge bomb
blast in east London on February 9.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor, which has voted against the act's renewal
since 1982, has changed its position.
</P>
<P>
Labor parliament members have been told not to vote against it,
according to a BBC TV report this afternoon. 
</P>
