<HEADLINE> Situation in Indonesia's Kimika Under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The situation in Tembagapura and
Timika, Irian Jaya, has been brought under control after several
days of rioting, Indonesia's top police officer said today.
</P>
<P>
But the situation there still needed to be watched closely,
said National Chief of Police Gen. Banurusman Astrosemirto,
quoting the head of the local police.
</P>
<P>
He said law and order had been restored in the city of
Tembagapura, including Timika subdistrict.
</P>
<P>
The riots that began last Sunday were triggered by rumors that
a local resident had been killed in an accident involving a car
belonging to the American Copper and Mining Company PT Freeport
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people stormed Freeport office buildings and
employees' houses, breaking facilities, properties and damaging
cars.
</P>
<P>
A dozen of people were injured in the clashes with police, with
two in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
At the peak of the riots on Monday and Tuesday, Freeport
Company and Mining was temporarily closed, so was the local
airport.  
</P>
</TEXT>
