<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Police Clashes with Clergyman's Supporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus anti-riot police clashed
today with the supporters of a clergyman, who appeared before the
Holy Synod, the supreme church body, facing charges of moral
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place when hundreds of people gathered
around the Archbishopric, in the walled city of Nicosia, to
support Archimandrite Pangratios Meraklis, who is a candidate for
the post of the Bishop of Morphou.
</P>
<P>
The anti-riot policemen used tear gas and clubs to disperse
the demonstrators as they were hurling stones, tomatoes and
fruits against police.
</P>
<P>
During the clash, a number of people, including policemen,
were injured and taken to Nicosia hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Archbishop Chrysostomos has claimed to have evidence that
Meraklis was a homosexual. However, Meraklis vehemently denied the
charge.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government has appealed for the restoration of law
and order and called on Meraklis' supporters to restrain
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides told the press that
"I am really saddened by today's incidents. On behalf of the
government, I would like to express sadness for today's events
outside the Archbishopric."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted the government had a duty to "act and calm
things down and I appeal to everybody to restore calm."
</P>
<P>
"We have often said demonstrators are free to express their
feelings but, it must be made clear that police cannot allow the
crowds to enter the Archbishopric. Law and order must prevail,
unfortunately we have no other choice," Cassoulides said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that several shops in the main shopping areas
of downtown Nicosia closed because of the riot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
