<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France's 1996 Growth Will Fall Short of Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- France's economic growth rate will
fall short of the projected 2.8 percent this year, Minister of
Economics and Finance Jean Arthuis said today.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimated that the growth rate would be a mere 1.5
percent in 1996, compared with 2.4 percent in 1995 and 2.9 percent
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, Arthuis stressed that the government would try to
slash public deficits to within 4 percent of GDP this year and 3
percent next year.
</P>
<P>
France's public debt in 1995 amounted to 600 billion
U.S. dollars, 40 percent of its GDP, which was below the European
Union's ceiling of 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
A report from France's Economic and Social Council said even if
the country's financial situation improved rapidly, its public
debt would continue snowballing until the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
