<HEADLINE> Individual Income Tax Cheat Sentenced to Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Wei Baolin, a senior engineer at
the Beijing Mining and Metallurgical Research Institute, is going
to have to serve two years in prison and pay 50,000 yuan in fines
for individual income tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's West District People's Court reached the verdict
today in the first instance of justice departments trying an
individual income tax case publicly, since administrative offices
for local taxes were established.
</P>
<P>
From October, 1992 to March, 1993, Wei had technology service
agreements with three companies in Guangdong, Jiangsu, and
Zhejiang provinces for the Zhenxing New Mining Technology
Development Company of Lengshuijiang City, Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
He received a total of 105,000 yuan for his services, but did
not report it to the local tax administration or pay for the part
of his taxes that was not covered by his employer and the three
companies.
</P>
<P>
According to the country's Criminal Law and tax evasion
regulations made by the NPC Standing Committee, the court ruled
that Wei was guilty of cheating on his taxes.
</P>
<P>
Yang Chunping, deputy director of Beijing's Administration of
Local Taxation, said that Beijing residents paid 320 million yuan
in individual income taxes last year, up 200 million yuan from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still many people who do not report their
income, but most taxes are withheld from employees' salaries by
their employers. As in many countries, it is still very difficult
to tax the upper-income bracket, because of their ability to
protect their income from disclosure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
