<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 58 Detained in Istanbul for Illegal Demonstration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Istanbul police have arrested 58
people who were involved in illegal demonstrations Wednesday night
which led to the injury of eight policemen.
</P>
<P>
According to a police statement issued today, the demonstrators
gathered without permission in the low-income neighborhoods of
Alibeykoy and Maltepe, chanting slogans to protest police who put
down the Gaziospanpasa rioting last year.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, most of them were members of outlawed
radical leftist organizations, built barricades and set fire to
tires to defy the intervention of local police.
</P>
<P>
The Anatolia news agency reported that at least eight
policemen were wounded when the demonstrators threw stones and
Molotov cocktails at security forces.
</P>
<P>
Istanbul police have clamped strict security in Gaziospanpasa
during the first anniversary of the rioting.
</P>
<P>
Some outlawed groups thus switched to other neighborhoods to
continue their protest against the government and local police,
whom they accused as "fascists."
</P>
<P>
During four days of rioting in March 1995, 21 Alevis, members
of a Moslem sect, were killed when police clashed with thousands
of people protesting the coffeehouse slaying of a community member
by unidentified gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Local media portrayed last year's rioting as "sectarian
violence" between Sunni and Alevi communities. But some analysts
said the rioting was in fact a result of unfair social system
which barred not only the Alevis but also all the poor population
from their rights of living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
