<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Curbs Soil Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Inner Mongolia, one of
China's worst hit areas for soil erosion, have made great efforts
to reclaim the land.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia loses an average of 300 million tons of soil a
year. The farmers and herdsmen have helped build reservoirs and
dams to help solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Now 42,000 square kilometers of Inner Mongolia's pastoral
lands, with its large tracts of desert, have been improved after a
10-year drive to fight soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said the most effective way to curb soil
erosion is to combine capital construction with biological means,
combine land improvements with closed-off afforested areas, and
combining water and soil conservation with land exploitation.
</P>
<P>
From 1985, the local government mobilized farmers and herdsmen
to build 87 water storage dams and reservoirs, which have retained
2.17 million cubic meters of silt in each of the past few years.
</P>
<P>
They have also planted grass on 734,000 hectares of land, and
built 391,300 hectares of cultivated land. The green cover rate
has risen from 21 percent to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the development of a diversified economy, the annual
per capita income of farmers has increased by more than five times
over the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
