<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kipketer not Permitted to Run for Denmark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Olympic Committee (KOC) on
Thursday formally rejected a request from its Danish counterpart
asking Kenya to permit world 800 meters champion Wilson Kipketer
to run for Denmark at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"The answer was "No'," said Charles Mukora, chairman of the
KOC. "To run for Denmark at an Olympics, Kipketer must wait for
the Sydney Games. ... We stick to the rules of the International
Olympic Committee (IOC)."
</P>
<P>
Olympic Charter ruled that a person could only compete for a
country three years after being granted full citizenship.
</P>
<P>
It means that Kipketer cannot run for Denmark at the Atlanta
Olympics even if he is granted full citizenship.
</P>
<P>
Mukora is also a member of the IOC board and council member of
the International Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF).
</P>
<P>
Kipketer has not met the seven-year residency period to qualify
for Danish citizenship and efforts to have the Danish parliament
process his application in time for Atlanta Games have so far
failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
