<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Desertification From Improper Water Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese researchers say that the
cause of the increasingly more severe desertification in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region over past two decades has
been irrational use of water resources.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey by the Xinjiang Institute of
Biology, Pedology, and Deserts under the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, most water in desert streams is either used up by
irrigation or held in reservoirs without passing through the
desert, resulting in deterioration because of drought and
diminishing ground cover.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that 20 years ago, desertification was
the product of warfare, excessive cutting of trees, and irrational
cultivation practices, which damaged vegetation, but in the past
20 years, the process was the result of water depletion.
</P>
<P>
It has been determined that 40 percent of desertified land in
the Taklimakan Desert, China's largest, is the result of such
irrational use of water.
</P>
<P>
The "green corridor" along the lower reaches of the Tarim River
is now deceasing and deserts at both sides of the corridor are
eating away at the oases at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Local governments are taking steps to develop more water
conservation projects and to raise the utility rate of water
resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
