<HEADLINE> Bank Chief Warns Against Rushing Into Monetary Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The governor of the Bank of
England, Eddie George, warned Wednesday of the economic risks of
pushing ahead with a single European currency by 1999 and said
Britain would not be damaged by opting out of the project.
</P>
<P>
Referring to rising unemployment in the European Union (EU),
George said recent developments had increased his doubts about
moving ahead with Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"If EMU goes wrong, it could become a serious source of
political discord within Europe rather than contributing to
European harmony," he told a Royal Institute of International
Affairs conference here.
</P>
<P>
The governor also clashed with his European counterparts by
insisting that the pound did not have to rejoin the Exchange Rate
Mechanism (ERM) in order to retain the option of taking part in a
single currency.
</P>
<P>
He said it would be mindless to insist that a currency which
had achieved stability outside the ERM be prevented from taking
part in the EMU.
</P>
<P>
If there were doubts about the likely success of the single
currency, George said, Britain should stay outside. With sensible
monetary policy at home, Britain would not suffer from remaining
outside, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no particular reason to suppose that the British
economy would be damaged by exercising that option," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
