<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old People Getting Healthier, Study Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Old people are getting healthier,
and extra years of life no longer mean extra years of disability,
an American survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Arthritis, high blood pressure, circulation problems, dementia,
stroke, blocked arteries and emphysema were becoming less
prevalent among the old every year, said Kenneth Manton of Duke
University in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
Manton has been conducting a survey of the health and
lifestyles of 20,000 American men and women over the age of 65
since 1982.
</P>
<P>
Medical problems doctors considered normal in 65-year-olds
often did not appear now until people were 70 or 75, Manton said
in a report in the New Scientist published here today.
</P>
<P>
"It raises the question of what should be considered normal
aging," he said.
</P>
<P>
Medical advances such as hip replacements and beta-blockers to
control high blood pressure were two obvious causes, he added, but
more subtle factors might be at work too.
</P>
<P>
Better nutrition in the early years of the century gave today's
old people a much better start in life than the previous
generation enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
However, not all diseases are in retreat. Some cancers and
bronchitis were increasing among the elderly, reflecting smoking
and air pollution, Manton said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the decline in the number of disabled
elderly had saved the U.S. government 200 billion dollars since
1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
