<HEADLINE> China Busy Inviting Bids for Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The race to win multi-million
dollar orders from China's Three Gorges Dam Project is to be
launched soon.
</P>
<P>
Companies from Germany, Japan, Canada, Russia and other
countries are already lining up on the starting line waiting for
the bidding to start in the second quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
China is inviting international bidding for the purchase of 14
water turbogenerators for the construction of the Three Gorges
Project, the world-largest water-control scheme.
</P>
<P>
Yangtze River Three Gorges Development Corporation, the major
undertaker of the project, describes the next round of bids as one
of several large-scale international contests the country will
invite for the project this year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, China invited international bidding for the
purchase of concrete lifting and transporting equipment. A dozen
manufacturers from the Republic of Korea, Japan, Russia, Germany,
and the United States competed for the bid.
</P>
<P>
China is evaluating the bids and is expected to announce the
results soon, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
In order to guarantee the successful damming of the Yangtze
River in 1997, China is busy inviting bids both at home and
abroad, in order to excavate earth and place concrete on schedule.
</P>
<P>
This year's domestic bids for the project include: second phase
of a cofferdam on the river, equipment for monitoring the security
of the project's water-conservancy system, construction of a dike
on the river's left bank, the third phase of the project's power
plant, among others.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of a permanent ship-lock whose bidding result
was announced in early March will involve a total investment 2.5
billion yuan (about 301 million US dollars). 
</P>
