<HEADLINE> Shanghai Steps Up Efforts to Improve Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has launched a
ten-billion yuan drive to improve its environment.
</P>
<P>
Although China's largest city has effectively put environmental
pollution under control, it should step up its efforts to embark
upon more environment-related projects to further improve the
environment, Gu Yongkang, official of the municipal environmental
protection bureau, said.
</P>
<P>
Projects for this year include sewage treatment, drinking water
improvement and afforestation, and will involve an investment of
more than ten billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, local authorities have spent five billion
yuan on environmental improvement. The relocation of polluting
factories is one of the major measures to improve the
environment. Since 1986 Shanghai has relocated 105 heavily
polluting factories, the resettlement of which cost 2.77 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Huangpu River is one of the major drinking water sources
for the 13 million urban residents. Over the past decade, some 40
industrial pollution sources and 80 domestic animal farms at the
upper reaches of the river have been treated, and the overall
discharge of pollutants brought under control. A 6,000-m long and
50-m wide green belt was also created to protect river sources.
</P>
<P>
The control of discharge of waste gases from motor vehicles is
also one of the focuses for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The environmental treatment relates not only to the improvement
of the investment environment but, more importantly, to the
improvement of the quality of life for local residents, said Gu
Yongkang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
