<HEADLINE> Forum on Mekong Subregion Development Held in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The third forum on investment
opportunities in the Greater Mekong Subregion (GMS) was held here
today with the participation of representatives from Cambodia,
China, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam as well as some 300
South Korean businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The one-day forum, co-sponsored by the Federation of Korean
Industries (FKI) and the Asian Development Bank (ADB), was
designed to explain the GMS projects sponsored by the ADB to South
Korean firms interested in possible investments.
</P>
<P>
The forum featured comprehensive presentations on the region's
developmental opportunities, particularly in transportation,
telecommunications, energy as well as the role of the ADB in such
development.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Asian and European leaders at the first
Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) in Bangkok agreed to develop the Mekong
subregion, an area bounded by Cambodia, China, Laos, Myanmar,
Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
In his welcoming address, FKI Chairman Chey Jong-hyon said,
"the South Korean business community is now considering the Mekong
river area as one of the most attractive areas."
</P>
<P>
"Korean businessmen are very well aware of the rich natural and
human resources in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Such economic potential, if combined with the experience and
top-of-the-line technology Korea has acquired during its
three-decade industrialization process, will certainly bring
economic prosperity to both the Mekong subregion and Korea," Chey
said.
</P>
<P>
The FKI chairman called for an active participation of
neighboring countries in GMS projects and assistance of
international financial organizations such as the ADB and the
International Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
</P>
<P>
Following Chey's keynote address, representatives of the six
countries delivered speeches and several ADB officials, including
Vice-President Noritada Morita, provided some background
information about the Mekong projects.
</P>
<P>
The fourth forum of its kind will be held in Manila, the
Philippines, late next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
