<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ports of Entry Development in Guangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region
in south China now has 28 ports of entry, which played a leading
part in the growth of local foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The region has nearly 1,595 km of coastal lines and 1,050 km of
land border lines.
</P>
<P>
There were only three ports before 1992, so the bulk of import
and export commodities had to be transfered to other provinces for
loading and unloading purposes, greatly restricting the
development of foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi now ranks the 3rd place according to the number of
ports of entry among all provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions in China, with 17 Category-A and 11 Category-B ports of
entry.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the role of the ports, the region reaped an aggregate
import and export volume of ten billion US dollars-worth during
the Eighth Five-Year Plan (1991-95), a 2.63 times increase over
the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
And last year a total of 977 million US dollars-worth of
exports were delivered from the ports, up 11 percent over 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
