<HEADLINE> Qingdao Port Able to Handle One Million TEUs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Qingdao Port, a major coastal
outlet in east China's Shandong Province, has become the first
harbor in the country capable of handling the world's most
advanced container ships.
</P>
<P>
The port now boasts an annual handling capacity of one million
TEUs. In 1995, the port handled 600,000 TEUs, up 40 percent from
1994.
</P>
<P>
The handling capacity of containers at Qingdao harbor, the
fifth largest port in China in terms of trade volume, has grown at
a record 30 to 40 percent during the past four years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, Qingdao has pumped three billion yuan into
revamping an old harbor area, and building a new one, raising the
port's annual handling capacity up to 51 million tons by the end
of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao Port now has three deep-water container berths equipped
with state-of-the-art container loading and unloading facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
