<HEADLINE> New Car Sales in Western Europe Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Western Europe saw an unexpected
sharp rise in new car sales last month, prompting carmakers into
believing that the industry's prospect this year might be less
pessimistic than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures released by the European Automobile
Manufacturers's Association show that new car registrations in
Western Europe last month rose by 10.2 percent to 1,041,500,
compared with 945,000 in February last year.
</P>
<P>
This lifted registrations for the first two months by 8.8
percent to 2,213,300, following a 6.7 per cent increase in January.
</P>
<P>
The recovery is being led by France where registrations jumped
by 17 percent last month following an 18.3 percent increase in
January.
</P>
<P>
In Germany, by far the region's single biggest car market, new
car sales last month rose by 9.5 percent to 264,000. For the first
two months as a whole, registrations in the country were 10.6
percent higher that a year ago.
</P>
<P>
New car sales in Spain, another major car market in Western
Europe, were also up strongly last month, with 13.7 percent
year-on-year, while those in Belgium, Finland, Ireland and Norway
all rose by more than 20 percent, according to the statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
