<HEADLINE> Experts Encouraged to Play Bigger Role in Jiangsu's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A "brain trust" of experts has
helped east China's Jiangsu Province make great strides.
</P>
<P>
The senior experts now have a say in government decision-making
on economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
So far, there have been more than 800 agents providing
consultations for governments at various levels across the
province, involving over 11,000 experts and professors.
</P>
<P>
With a total of 70,000 senior scientific and technological
experts, Jiangsu has been practicing a policy during the past few
years, encouraging experts to offer advices on economic and social
development.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of last year, 38 academicians, 46 middle-aged
and young experts, who have outstanding achievements and 15
celebrities became members of the province's first brain trust.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, they presented more than 200 proposals,
concerning the overall and long-term development of science and
technology, the internationalization of the local economy, and the
common progress of regional economies.
</P>
<P>
A beach development proposal has resulted in a provincial plan
for the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996--2000) to enclose 39,000
ha of tideland, develop 10,500 ha of enclosed idle land, and
transform 20,000 ha of middle- and low-yield land.
</P>
<P>
Experts in various cities and counties also enjoy a say in
local government decisions.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the consultancy committee composed of 39
experts in Nanjing, capital city of Jiangsu, offered their
opinions on more than 170 projects, which added a total economic
benefit valued at about 100 million yuan (nearly 12 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some cities and counties have started to seek senior
consultants from all over the country, as well as across the world.
</P>
<P>
Haimen City employed 134 experts in a bid to boost its economy,
mainly in material industry.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou City invited the world-renowned architect Ieoh Ming Pei
to be a consultant to help protect and build this historic city.
</P>
</TEXT>
