<HEADLINE> China Works to Protect Large Historical Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- China has worked out
detailed plans to protect large historical sites which have long
been regarded as the hardest of cultural relics to conserve.
</P>
<P>
Large historical sites include tribal sites, city ruins, and
remains of military defence works, water conservancy facilities,
mines, and groups of palaces.
</P>
<P>
China has around 200 large historical sites, accounting for
more than one third of the total cultural sites under state
protection.
</P>
<P>
To avoid conflicts between the protection of cultural relics
and the increasing demand for land in the light of rapid economic
development, departments of cultural property have made close
explorations at the sites. They have made it clear which parts of
the sites should be protected.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been made to solve problems of damage to the
environment of the sites. Beijing, for example, has stopped
production at several factories because they were blamed for air
pollution at the Zhoukoudian site, where Peking Man lived some
450,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province, where
a great number of large historical sites are located, 2,000 square
meters of new buildings at a group of imperial palaces of the Tang
Dynasty (618-907) have been dismantled.
</P>
<P>
The country has also encouraged local people to take part in
the protection of the sites.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an hired local farmers to work as guardians of the sites,
and mobilized locals to help develop tourism at the sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
