<HEADLINE> Harford Charged with Misconduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Wimbledon veteran Mick Harford
was charged with misconduct on Thursday following a F.A. Cup
quarter-final between the team and Chelsea on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old striker, who has 14 days to appeal, is in
trouble with the Football Association for an insulting gesture at
Chelsea fans rather than a verbal assault on the Chelsea's
manager Glenn Hoddle.
</P>
<P>
An angry Harford, who had just been substituted, had to be
pulled away from the Chelsea bench, when with language described
as "vile and atrocious" he allegedly accused Hoddle of having
"sorted" the referee in his favour.
</P>
<P>
"Mick Harford has been charged with misconduct for giving a
two-fingered gesture to the crowd when he was substituted during
Saturday's Cup tie," said F.A. spokesman Steve Double.
</P>
<P>
"He is charged with bringing the game into disrepute for the
gesture rather than the verbal outburst on the evidence of the
fourth official."
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon disputed the referee's decision to penalise them for
a back pass handled by their goalkeeper from which Ruud Gullit put
Chelsea ahead from a free kick.
</P>
<P>
But Wimbledon stormed back to equalise and earn a replay at
their Selhurst Park ground next Wednesday. 
</P>
