<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pledges Anti-Terrorism Aid to Israel (by Xie Dongfeng, Huai Chengbo) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
announced here today that the United States will commit more than
100 million U.S. dollars to assist Israel in the fight against
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Last night, I sent to the congress an emergency request for
the first installment for this counter-terrorism effort," said
Clinton at a press conference along with Israeli Prime Minister
Shimon peres.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president said he expected the congress to react
quickly to this important measure.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said that the U.S. and Israel will immediately
begin negotiations to conclude the bilateral agreement on
combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
According to Clinton, the agreement will strengthen the joint
U.S.-Israeli anti-terrorism effort in three areas.
</P>
<P>
"First, the U.S. will immediately begin to provide Israel with
additional equipment and training," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, our (two) nations will join together to develop new
anti-terrorism methods and technology, thirdly, we will work to
enhance communications and coordination between our (two) nations
as well as other nations who have joined us in the war against
terrorism," he added.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the U.S. will also increase its intelligence
sharing and coordination (with other nations on combating
terrorism)," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He said that U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who
is accompanying his 22-hour visit to Israel, will remain in
Israel to finalize details of the document.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. President stressed that the U.S. and Israel will make
every possible effort to defeat Islamic extremists and to prevent
them from killing innocent people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton stressed that the Middle East peace process
must continue. Without peace, there will be no security, and
without security, there will be no peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived here Wednesday night, after attending the
one-day international Summit of Peacemakers in Egyptian resort
Sharm el-Sheikh, to show his support for Israel in the aftermath
of the recent Hamas suicide bombing attacks in Israel which killed
58 people.
</P>
<P>
At today's press conference, Peres praised Clinton as "the
first world leader to put on his agenda peace in our time is a
major goal."
</P>
<P>
Turning to the Israeli closure on the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip, Peres said that it is not aimed at the Palestinian people,
but to "answer some security needs."
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to create no starvation," he said. "This is
clearly a security measure."
</P>
<P>
As to Syria, Peres said that while Damascus must press to
depart from support or shelter for terrorism, the door must be
left open for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Clinton shrugged off criticism by the Israeli opposition that
his visit here is merely to boost Peres' prospects in the
upcoming general elections in May.
</P>
<P>
He said he came here because terrorist attacks kill dozens of
people and because the U.S. is committed to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
He added that he will not interfere with Israeli internal
policies. "I respect the results of democracy here and at home,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Clinton attended a special Israeli cabinet
meeting, and discussed with Peres and his security advisers on
the situation regarding the suicide bombing attacks.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Clinton also met with opposition Likud Chairman
Binyamin Netanyahu and Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. President is scheduled to leave Israel for Washington
this afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
