<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Urged to Control Maputo River's Displacement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has requested that
South Africa should control the discharging capacity of the upper
reaches of Maputo River so as to prevent the areas of the lower
reaches in Mozambique from being flooded.
</P>
<P>
Xavier Junior, leader for water resources of the National
Water Conservency Authority said he told South Africa that
Mozambique cannot stand the water displacement of 800 cubic
meters/a second from Maputo River as the lower reaches would be
flooded.
</P>
<P>
He said this after South Africa informed him that as from
March 13, South Africa would displace 800 cuber meters of water
per second from the upper reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Junior said he had asked South Africa to lower the discharging
capacity to the level of below 600 cubic meters per second and is
waiting for a reply.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains in central and south Mozambique since January have
caused rivers to overflow, displacing more than 200,000 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
