<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Young Scientists Selected for CAS Priority Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Twenty outstanding young Chinese
scientists, including nine who have studied and worked overseas,
have been selected by the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) for a
maximum funding of about two million yuan each.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the selection results today, Lu Yongxiang, CAS
executive vice-president, said the 20 young scientists, whose ages
range between 29-39, will have better working and living
conditions because of the funding, than most of their domestic
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The funding, which varies to meet the demands of different
branches of science, will be used to start up their research, buy
necessary equipment and instruments for experiments and houses for
their own use.
</P>
<P>
The selection was the second made by CAS as part of its plan to
train 100 leaders in various branches of sciences by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The academy chose 14 young Chinese scientists from both home
and abroad in late 1994, the first such effort since the plan was
launched in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Xie Jinchun, 33, member of American Physics Society, and winner
of first Wu Chien-shiung Physics Prize, is among the nine
scientists who have made outstanding achievements during study and
work abroad. Xie returned to China last month.
</P>
<P>
Lu said CAS encourages excellent young scientists in and
outside China, who have not been chosen but are interested in
working for CAS, to work at the academy.
</P>
<P>
He promised that CAS will provide them with similar or even
better working and living conditions than those included in the
plan in accordance with the needs of CAS research.
</P>
<P>
The academy, which has about 60,000 researchers, also plans to
train 2,000 leading scientists and 30,000 young scientific workers
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
CAS is scheduled to recruit 26 young Chinese scientists
studying and working at home and abroad this year, and offer
similar treatment, the vice-president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
