<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mountainous Areas in Hebei Province Become Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Barren mountains in north
China's Hebei Province have become green as a result of a massive
afforestation project launched by farmers.
</P>
<P>
One of the afforestation projects - costing over 300 million
yuan - was designed to provide a shelterbelt of trees north of
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Hebei Provincial Forestry Department said
that the provincial government had launched the afforestation
project in 1986 in a 100,000 sq km area in the Yanshan, Hengshan
and Taihang mountains. Trees have so far been planted on 1.2
million hectares of land and grass on 33,000 hectares in the 50
counties in the area.
</P>
<P>
Experts say 99 percent of the trees planted so far have
survived.
</P>
<P>
The province has also created 340 woods so far.
</P>
<P>
An effective measure taken by the provincial government to
afforest barren hills is to ban livestock grazing and firewood
gathering on mountains, the official said.
</P>
<P>
To date, the acreage of enclosed mountainsides, totalling
840,000 ha, accounts for 34 percent of the province's total
afforested acreage.
</P>
<P>
Air tree seeding on mountains is conducted in the rainy season,
creating woods of 67,000 ha every year, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In a move to quicken the pace of tree planting, local
governments began to sell rights to use barren hills and wasteland
to farmers and enterprises in 1993. As a result, over 600 million
yuan has been raised for afforestation, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
