<HEADLINE> Fighting Renews in Grozny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between Russian
government troops and Chechen separatists flared up again early
today in central Grozny, capital of the breakaway Russian
republic, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The clash renewed at 10:00 Moscow time (07:00 GMT) on the eve
of a crucial meeting of the decision-making Russian Security
Council, which is to approve a peace scenario for the Chechen
settlement.
</P>
<P>
An exchange of fire occurred when armed separatists loyal to
rebel leader Dzhokhar Dudayev opened fire from a 16-story building
on a Russian checkpoint on a bridge over the Sunzha river close to
the Minutka Square in downtown Grozny, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Clashes were also reported in a neighborhood in eastern Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev is in Grozny for talks
with Chechen leaders to find a way of curbing the new wave of
separatist attacks on the city.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, hundreds of Chechen rebels started a major
assault on Grozny also on the eve of a Russian Security Council
meeting. The fighting raged for four days in the city, causing
numerous casualties on both sides as well as to local residents.
</P>
<P>
Russian troops delivered air and artillery strikes on Chechen
separatists' positions in Bamut, 35 kilometers southwest of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
The Russian command believes that Bamut, a one-time Soviet
missile base, is where the Chechen separatists' main ammunition
and weapons dumps are located. It is the last major stronghold of
the rebels after their base in Novogroznensky was eliminated.
</P>
</TEXT>
