<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Firms Cracks Down on Software Pirates in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's main software companies
have set up a watchdog organization to fight against software
piracy in this country.
</P>
<P>
Business Software Alliance (BSA) Turkey, founded by 14 local
and foreign software companies recently, will take legal actions
to crack down on pirates of software in Turkey, today's Turkish
Daily News quoted Emre Berkin, General Manager of Microsoft
Bilgisayar Yazilim Hizmetleri Ltd, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The computer company is a Turkish subsidiary of the world's
leading computer software producer Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
BSA Turkey intends to protect over 10 brands of software
programs currently sold in Turkey from illegal copy and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
Berkin said "BSA Turkey aims to reduce copyright violations
software and encourage greater use of licensed programs," adding
that infringement of software copyright is widespread in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Some 95 percent of all software used in desk top processors or
personal computers in Turkey have been illegally obtained and
about 30 percent of Microsoft's DOS and Windows programs have
been pirated, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Pirated software costs producers of programs billions of
U.S. dollars in lost revenue worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the European Union have singled out
Turkey as one of the world's worst violators of software
copyright.
</P>
<P>
Turkish parliament last June worked out a new law protecting
copyrights and intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
The new law forbids illegal copying, distribution, sale and use
of copyrighted software.
</P>
<P>
Those who are involved in software pirates cases will face up
to three years imprisonment and must pay hefty fines if found
guilty of copyright infringement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
