<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Planting the Seeds of a New Idea in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- People often celebrate special
occasions with flowers. But in Shanghai they are branching out
into a new craze ... saying it with trees.
</P>
<P>
Couples celebrating golden wedding anniversaries and proud
grandparents wishing birthday greetings to their grandchildren are
digging deep to add more greenery to the landscape of China's
biggest city.
</P>
<P>
A plot of land in the western part of Shanghai has been
assigned for residents to plant commemorative trees.
</P>
<P>
With less than one-and-a-half square meters of green land per
person, Shanghai is much in need of an injection of grass and tree-

covered areas.
</P>
<P>
A local green land development corporation developed the plot
of the land, and invited people to plant commemorative trees.
</P>
<P>
The initiative received a good response from residents and
telephones lines at the corporation rang non-stop with people
placing orders.
</P>
<P>
The corporation provides 16 species of trees for people to
choose. People can attach commemorative plaques to the trees,
which record names, dates, and commemorative messages.
</P>
<P>
With a cost of up to 500 yuan(60 US dollars), hundreds of
people have ordered trees, and more than 100 commemorative trees
are already growing on the land.
</P>
<P>
Among the people who planted trees, there are grandmothers
planting birthday trees for grandsons; friends planting friendship
trees; old couples planting trees celebrating golden wedding
anniversaries.
</P>
<P>
With the help of his grandmother and mother, Zhangqi, a
five-year-old boy from Hongkou District, planted a metasequoia to
commemorate his birthday.
</P>
<P>
Asked why he chose to plant the metasequoia, he said:" It grows
up rapidly and uprightly. I also want to grow up quickly to be an
upright person." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttling Mps Costs Malawi Dearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Administrative costs of
Malawi parliament are likely to be the highest in Africa,
Tanzanian official news agency "Shihata" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Shihata reported that large amounts of money paid as travel
allowances to members of the house between Zomba and other parts
of Malawi is the cause of the high costs.
</P>
<P>
Shihata quoted an official of the eastern and southern African
universities research program, Ms. Florence Swai as saying the
parliament building was in Zomba although there are no
residential facilities for the members of the house.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarians have to travel daily to attend sessions
there, Ms. Swai added.
</P>
<P>
Shihata further said between 50 and 70 members drive from
Blantyre daily during the session, while those without means of
transport hire some. Blantyre is 70 kilometers from Zomba.
</P>
<P>
Shihata added that it costs 1,000 Kwachas (about 66 US
Dollars) to hire a car from Blantyre to Zomba for a single trip.
The government pays 132 dollars per day on transport allowance to
the parliamentarians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
