<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0830 GMT, March 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The strike of the General Motors (GM) union
workers entered the 9th day Wednesday, paralyzing most of the GM
assembly plants in North American as the world's largest automaker.
</P>
<P>
By Wednesday, 22 of GM's 29 North American assembly plants had
stopped working due to the run-out of parts made at Dayton. Dozens
of GM's other parts plants were closing or curtailing production.
</P>
<P>
About 90,000 GM workers were off the job Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. multimillionaire magazine publisher Steve
Forbes has decided to quit race for the Republican presidential
nomination and throw his support to U.S. Senate Republican Leader
Bob Dole, his aides said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Forbes, who had spent some 30 million U.S. dollars since he
announced his participation in the campaign last September, made
the decision one day after Dole swept the Republican primaries in
seven states on so-called "Super Tuesday."
</P>
<P>
Forbes campaign manager Bill Dal Col told reporters that Forbes
himself will make the retreat announcement sometime on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French President Jacques Chirac and German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl both hailed Wednesday's international anti-terrorist
"Summit of the Peacemakers" in Egypt as a success.
</P>
<P>
Chirac told reporters today that the meeting of the peacemakers
is in itself progress in the peace process after the force of
hatred gained the upper hand for a while.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl described as "remarkable" the
four-hour summit in the Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh which
was attended by 27 nations.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- NATO and U.N. representatives said Wednesday that
gangs arriving from Sarajevo were looting houses and terrorizing
Serbs remaining in Ilidza, a Serb suburb which was transfered to
the Muslim-Croat federation on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
International Police Force Commissioner Peter Fitzgerald told
reporters that federation police arrested several persons today
who were looting houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
