<HEADLINE> Beijing Announces Traffic Measures to Protect Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- New steps aimed at guaranteeing
road safety of primary and secondary school students will take
effect here soon, according to "Beijing Daily".
</P>
<P>
One thousand placards with the Chinese character "rang",
meaning "give way", were given to students Monday so that they can
show them to drivers while crossing roads.
</P>
<P>
During school hours police officers will be specially
designated to escort school children across the roads in front of
20 schools, where road conditions are complicated and accidents
are common, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a total of 500,000 yuan (about 60,000 US dollars)
has been spent setting up 103 zebra crossings and 307
traffic signs in front of 162 primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 400,000 copies of a letter on road safety have
been sent to drivers and parents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
