<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 08:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Key Granary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural experts in Central
China's Hunan Province are streaming to rural areas to spread
latest research findings. The aim is to help farmers with spring
farming despite freezing wet weather.
</P>
<P>
"I feel just like fish in water when I am here," said Zhou
Yingbin, associate research fellow of the Hunan Agricultural
University, while teaching eagerly-learning farmers how to soak
seeds and raise rice seedlings.
</P>
<P>
Zhou disclosed that he and colleagues are putting into practice
a "national rice project," which they developed recently under the
leadership of Yuan Longping, known as "father of hybrid rice".
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to help add 3.2 billion kilograms of
grain to Hunan's present annual output of 27 billion kilograms of
rice by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of Hunan's efforts to increase the grain output,
and serve as one of China's key granaries in the next century,"
said Pang Daomu, deputy governor of the province.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include tapping the land resources, using
science to raise the level of crops from single output units, and
to arouse the enthusiasm of farmers.
</P>
<P>
With arable land accounting for only 3.2 percent of China's
total, Hunan produces six percent of the nation's total grain, and
its rice output ranks first in the country.
</P>
<P>
Tan Qiucheng, an official of Hunan Provincial Bureau of
Agriculture, said the grain-sufficient province has sold an annual
of five billion kilograms of grain to the state and other
provinces and regions, exclusive of the amount of grain sold by
farmers themselves.
</P>
<P>
"The amount of grain is enough to feed 125 million people a
year, and we shall contribute more grain in the future," the
deputy governor added.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have estimated that Hunan's maximal potential of
grain output will be 36 billion kilograms annually.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the grain production, the province plans to open up
the remaining 200,000 hectares of areas suitable for farming,
raise the multiple crop index and single output units, and spread
the cultivation of hybrid rice.
</P>
<P>
This year will witness the province popularizing such skills as
 sparsely-planting rice on dry farmland, throwing rice shoots in
the field, and second cropping rice, known as "ratooning rice"
academically.
</P>
<P>
Farmers are encouraged to raise more pigs, and process and
market grain to make more profits out of grain.
</P>
<P>
While designating farmland protection zones, improving
cultivation methods, and making full use of local resources, the
provincial government has set up grain funds by charging a grain
consumption tax, and urging industry to support agriculture. It
also diverted foreign interest in investing in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"With the implementation of all policies in favor of
agriculture, we shall be able to boost the grain output, with our
research findings leading in the world," said Yuan Longping, the
well-known agricultural scientist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 07:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Orchestras to Create Symphony Music Tide in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Tours by four of the world's top
symphony orchestras to China this year are expected to start a
wave of following for classical music.
</P>
<P>
The treat for music lovers starts with a high note next month
when the Orchestra National De France visits China.
</P>
<P>
In June the Philadelphia Orchestra from the USA will head east,
followed in September by the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra. The
musical tide will reach its finale in October with a visit by the
Wiener Philharmoniker.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of the Chinese Ministry of Culture, the
orchestras will demonstrate their virtuosity to Chinese music
lovers under separate batons of Charles Dutoit, Wolfgang
Sawallisch, Riccardo Chailly and Zubin Mehta during the '96
Beijing International Symphony Music Year, sponsored by the China
Performing Arts Agency.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the visits of the four orchestras will
stir up a craze for symphony music among Chinese people for a
third time since 1973 and 1979 when several foreign orchestras
visited China, broadening the vision of the Chinese music circle.
</P>
<P>
An official with China's Ministry of Culture described the
season of concerts as a symbol of the opening of a new era for
China's cultural exchanges, describing as unprecedented, the
visits by four first-level orchestras all within a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Finance Seen Stable in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- China's finance will perform
stably in the first quarter of this year, statistics released by
the State Information Center (SIC) show.
</P>
<P>
Bank deposits are expected to rise 30 percent to 4.1617
trillion yuan. The rise, however, will be weaker than in the
previous quarter because the expansion in deposits has slowed down
and residents have less money to deposit.
</P>
<P>
Bank loans are expected to jump 21 percent to 3.9849 trillion
yuan, of which short-term loans will expand 20.5 percent to 2.9101
trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Currency in circulation is expected to grow a paltry 9.6
percent to 797.3 billion yuan, as China has vowed to stick to its
tight monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Increases in price subsidies to beat inflation will be smaller
as price hike will slow down, and increases in tax revenues will
not rise dramatically as the economy will grow at a slower pace
and tax revenues already rocketed in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
In this quarter tax revenues are expected to hit 113.6 billion,
up 10.6 percent, and government expenditure will be 110 billion
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
