<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading A. African Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading South African newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen
</P>
<P>
-- South Africa's 1996/97 budget, announced by Finance
Minister Chris Liebenberg yesterday, was welcomed by markets with
the local currency Rand strengthened by 3.5 cent against the US
Dollar, but criticized by many politicians and businessmen
concerning various elements.
</P>
<P>
-- The African National Congress yesterday refused to attend a
constitutional committee meeting in Kwazulu/Natal provincial
legislature and said the province ''might be in hard times''
without its support for the proposed constitution.
</P>
<P>
The Star
</P>
<P>
-- South Africa's new budget, introduced in Parliament by
Finance Minister Chris Liebenberg yesterday, saw a modest rise in
real expenditure, a reduction of the deficit and a commitment of
more efficient tax collection.
</P>
<P>
Business Day
</P>
<P>
-- South Africa's organized labor yesterday gave a cautious
welcome to the 1996/97 budget, announced by Finance Minister
Chris Liebenberg in Parliament, saying an attempt had been made
to shift the burden from the poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
