<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reserve Zone Set up to Protect Classic-Style City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Official protection is to be
given to a corner of an ancient Chinese city known as 'the Venice
of the East'.
</P>
<P>
The Suzhou city government has issued details of the project,
and noted American architect, Ieoh Ming Pei, has been hired to
help in a program to create a special reserve zone in Suzhou, in
Jiangsu Province, to protect historical buildings and streets.
</P>
<P>
The zone covers the eastern part of the city near the Pingjiang
River, including one garden, five waterways, 12 stone bridges and
16 buildings in the styles of the Ming dynasty (1368-1644) and the
Qing dynasty (1644-1919).
</P>
<P>
The history of the city dates to 2,500 years ago. Protected
houses and buildings are mostly intact, with upturned eaves, white
walls, black tiles, and windows and doors decorated with wood
carvings.
</P>
<P>
The distribution and the style are very similar to those on a
map from the Song dynasty(960-1279).
</P>
<P>
The program aims at developing local tourism, improving the
environment and protecting historical relics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
