<HEADLINE> Hubei's High Speed Mail Service Takes Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Jet-speed postal services from
central China have won a stamp of approval from customers.
</P>
<P>
A new service means that letters can travel half way around the
world in as little as two days.
</P>
<P>
Middle China's Hubei Province has expanded its direct air-mail
inter-exchange and EMS services to four more foreign countries-
Japan, Singapore, Australia and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The boost comes a year after the province launched the service
by introducing high-speed postal links with the USA and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The province's air-mail and EMS letters can directly reach the
additional four countries within two or three days through the
Wuhan Emergency Mail Service Bureau. It used to take four or five
days for such letters to arrive previously.
</P>
<P>
Post offices in Beijing, Guangzhou, Shanghai handle most of the
country's international postal matters. It meant that the
province's international air-mails could only reach their
destinations via the three cities until now.
</P>
<P>
The province has also witnessed a boom in international postal
articles sent in recent years. The number topped 16 million last
year, about 60 percent of them bound for the six countries.
</P>
<P>
People can also inquire about their letters through computer
networks, as part of another improvement in the system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
