<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 07:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Tianjin College Students Seeing Psychologists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- It's the end of the work day, but
Dr. Li Huiqin, a psychologist in Nankai University's clinic, has
just finished two hours' talks with a frowning girl who has
been haunted by failing on several exams.
</P>
<P>
The doctor noted that, because of the increasing number of
college students visiting the psychology clinic, she often has to
leave work late.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the clinic is open twice a week, and eight to 10
students usually come each time.
</P>
<P>
At neighboring Tianjin University, some 1,000 undergraduates
and graduate students have seen a psychologist in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese college students have got accustomed to consultations
with a psychologist and to treatment. One girl said that she and
her classmates trust psychologists very much and are glad to be
able to talk with them.
</P>
<P>
The situation was different when the clinic at Tianjin
University opened 10 years ago. One doctor explained that, at that
time, many students knew very little about psychological
outpatient services, or misunderstood them. Some students thought
that only those who were insane went to see psychologists, so few
dared to go for visits.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey done by Tianjin's public health departments has
shown that some 16 percent of the city's college students have
psychological problems or diseases to differing degrees, such as
obsessive behaviour, neuroses, anxieties, depression,
schizophrenia, or other abnormal conditions.
</P>
<P>
One teacher attributes the increase in the number of
psychological disorders to the rapidly changing society and the
reforms, and to the necessity of seeking a job in the market
economy, the heavy schoolwork, and problems that occur during
puberty.
</P>
<P>
This situation has aroused the attention of school
administrators. Nankai University has, for the past several years,
conducted psychological tests on incoming freshmen and has kept a
record of their psychological conditions, in an attempt to deal
with problems when they occur.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's universities and colleges have also started to
provide public information about mental health through lectures
and by providing courses, which have been welcomed by students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
