<HEADLINE> Mugabe For Improvement Of Women's Social Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President robert
Mugabe has assured Zimbabwean women that his government was fully
behind all efforts to improve the status of women in society and
was committed to implementing recommendations adopted at the
Fourth World Conference for Women in Beijing, China, last year.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe made the commitment while addressing women, most of
whom are ZANU (PF) Women's League members, gathered to
commemorate the International Women's Day in Harare on Wednesday,
</P>
<P>
Mugabe's remarks are a repercussion to the facts that domestic
violence and sexual abuse against women and children have reached
intolerable and alarming levels.
</P>
<P>
He said women should come up with recommendations for stiff
penalties for perpetrators of these crimes and ''it would be
negation of duty on the part of the government to let these
people go unpunished, let alone destroy the family which is the
backbone of our society.''
</P>
<P>
The government would make everything possible to strengthen
its contribution and that of the non-governmental community in
helping victims of domestic violence and sexual abuse through
provision of proper counselling and sympathy, he said.
</P>
<P>
''What is more chilling is that most of the perpetrators of
these anti-social acts are relatives of the women and children
concerned in whom society has vested the responsibility of
protecting these weaker members of our society,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
