<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 06:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sky's the Limit For Elevator Companies in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- China is set to take a giant step
forward in the market for elevators.
</P>
<P>
The growth of high-rise cities will give a real lift to demand
for elevators in the next five years. An estimated 200,000 will be
needed by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The annual growth in demand for elevators across China will be
at least 10 percent in the 1996-2000 period, the country's Ninth
Five-Year Plan, a national survey revealed.
</P>
<P>
China's elevator industry experienced rapid development over
the past 16 years, with an aggregated output of 194,000. The
annual production spiralled to 30,000 in 1995, 13 times the 1980
figure.
</P>
<P>
Of the 123 registered elevator manufacturers in China, five are
Sino-foreign joint ventures, who possess a team of experienced
technicians, and up-to-date equipment. Their production makes up
60 percent of supplies on the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Though China has become the third largest elevator producer in
the world after the United States and Japan, it can hardly satisfy
the growing need for high-grade elevators and escalators on the
domestic market.
</P>
<P>
This can be attributed to the speed in the pace of
urbanization. Statistics show that the number of new cities will
soar to 800 by the year 2000. New buildings covering a total floor
space of 1.2 billion square meters will be completed in the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
Some large cities, including Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou and
Chongqing, are building or making plans for skyscrapers with
heights exceeding 300 meters.
</P>
<P>
Because of the immense demand, and shortage of high-quality
products, China will import 7,000 or 8,000 elevators from abroad
in each of the next few years. Elevator spare parts will also be
in great demand in China, according to a report in China Import
News.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
