<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 06:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GM Union Strike Enters 9th Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The strike of the General
Motors (GM) union workers entered the 9th day today, paralyzing
most of the GM assembly plants in North American as the world's
largest automaker.
</P>
<P>
By Wednesday, 22 of GM's 29 North American assembly plants had
stopped working due to the run-out of parts made at Dayton. Dozens
of GM's other parts plants were closing or curtailing production.
</P>
<P>
About 90,000 GM workers were off the job Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some of 1,600 companies that make parts for GM
cars have begun laying off their workers. ITT Automotive, which
makes brakes, said 370 employees at its plant in New Lexington,
Ohio, have been told not to work on Monday. A decision is pending
on layoffs at another ITT plant in Rochester, New York.
</P>
<P>
The strike's ripples have also affected the companies that
provide the raw materials and components for parts and at
thousands of GM dealerships where customers will not be able to
get specific models or options because no new vehicles are coming
into the inventory.
</P>
<P>
The walkout by some 3,000 members of the United Auto Workers
(UAW) at the two brake plants in Delphi Chassisin, Dayton, Ohio,
kicked off on March 5, mainly over job security and outsourcing,
the production of parts by outside plants or companies.
</P>
<P>
A GM spokesman said no significant progress was made Wednesday
and no new talks were scheduled for solving the crisis.
</P>
<P>
GM has been under heavy pressure from the financial community
to reduce its costs for components. Having UAW workers build the
parts at its own plants can cost virtually more than buying them
from outside suppliers that pay wages and benefits far below the
40-45 dollars hourly union salaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
