<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Amend Foreign Investment Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is to amend its investment
law so as to attract more foreign money, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Nhac, deputy head of the ministry for planning and
investment, said that Vietnam will funnel more investment to
projects vital to national development.
</P>
<P>
He said that Vietnam now needs "quality more than quantity" of
foreign investment which will be directed to projects which
Vietnamese entrepreneurs lack the means to undertake.
</P>
<P>
The country will create favorable conditions for foreign
investors in projects of significant interest to national
development.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to develop and foster industries in rural areas will
also be encouraged, as will moves to modernize and commercialize
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Prices and policies concerning land use may be revised to
encourage the growing of fruit trees and cash crops.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18 billion U.S. dollars poured into 1,325 investment
projects in the country as of last December.
</P>
<P>
Some investment projects will be left open to foreign investors
while others will only accept funds from local entrepreneurs after
the investment law is amended, Nhac added.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will help Vietnamese enterprises acquire shares in
all projects of infrastructure construction, including
build-operate-transfer projects funded by money from overseas.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam first pronounced its foreign investment law at the end
of 1987.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is reviewing the existing law and considering
amendments and supplements to be submitted to the National
Assembly for approval by the end of the year, he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
