<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Business Leaders Urge Opposition to  Further Relax Non-Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi business leaders
Wednesday urged the country's mainstream opposition parties to
make more relaxation in their indefinite non-cooperation campaign
to allow normal operation of more business entities.
</P>
<P>
The opposition launched the strike-like campaign last Saturday
to press for the scrapping of the parliamentary elections on
February 15, which were won by the ruling Bangladesh Nationalist
Party with the opposition parties boycotting.
</P>
<P>
The Chambers of Commerce and Employers' Association appreciated
in a statement the opposition's relaxation move Tuesday allowing
all banks, shops and export-oriented private factories to start
operations at a stipulated time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The association, however, said relaxation was also needed on
ports, financial institutions and public transports carrying
export cargoes to and from the ports.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the opposition to allow normal operations of
domestic-market-oriented industries and shops for the benefit of
millions of workers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce
and Industry (FBCCI), a leading body of the country's business
community, once again called upon President Rahman Biswas to take
measures for holding fresh elections under a neutral government.
</P>
<P>
FBCCI President Salman F. Rahman warned that a sit-in would be
staged in front of the Presidential House Saturday if the demand
was not met.  
</P>
