<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Indonesia Jointly to Curb Illegal Logging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian and Indonesian
armed forces will step up their cooperation to more effectively
curb illegal logging activities in Malaysia's Sarawak-Indonesia
border areas, Malaysia's news agency Bernama said today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Malaysia's Regional Two Commander Abdul Aziz
Hassan as saying that both countries would conduct more joint
military surveillance at the border checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Indonesia's Tanjungpura District
Sixth Military Commander Namuri Anoem in Kuching today, Abdul Aziz
said the two sides had agreed that top officials of the armed
forces of both countries would meet more often to discuss new
strategies and ways to check illegal logging.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed that Malaysian and Indonesian armed
forces should seek new ways to enhance military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Namuri arrived in Kuching Wednesday on a five-day working
visit, Bernama added.  
