<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 05:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crimea Doubts Quick Passage of Constitution by Kiev </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The parliamentary speaker of Crimean
Autonomous Republic doubted today that the Ukrainian Supreme
Soviet (parliament) will approve a new Crimean constitution in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference in the Crimean capital of Simferopol,
Yevgeny Suprunyuk asked Kiev to handle its relations with Crimea
in a constructive way and not to escalate the longstanding
constitutional row.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian parliament abolished Crimea's 1992 constitution
in March 1995, accusing it of assisting the separationist tendency
in the mainly ethnic Russian peninsula. The parliament also passed
a law on Crimea status, demanding Crimea produce a constitution on
the basis of the law.
</P>
<P>
But last month, the Ukrainian Constitutional Committee
suggested the new constitution drafted by the Crimean parliament
be changed into a "charter" for further revision.
</P>
<P>
To this, the Crimean parliament stated this week that Crimea's
right to a referendum on its status should not be written off from
any new constitution and urged Kiev to pass the one it drafted by
the month end.
</P>
<P>
The current constitutional row has roused deep concerns of
President Leonid Kuchma and Chairman of the Supreme Soviet
Alexander Moroz, who called for restraints from the
parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
The Crimean Peninsula was part of Russia before 1954 when it
was incorporated into Ukraine under the then Soviet leadership.
</P>
<P>
It then tried to return to Russia's fold despite its autonomous
status Kiev was forced to give in 1992. Separatist movement in the
peninsula suffered a great setback after Ukraine suspended both
Crimea's constitution and its presidency in March 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 05:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Group to Work on Rating System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A group headed by Jack
Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of America
(MPAA), was set up today to develop a system for rating sex and
violence in television shows.
</P>
<P>
The group's tasks, expected to be completed by the end of the
year, include deciding what shows should be rated.
</P>
<P>
Executives of the group have said sports and news won't be
rated, but no consensus has been reached on how to treat cartoons,
children's shows and news magazines.
</P>
<P>
The rating will involve shows on broadcast, cable and public
television and is supposed to be applied by the program's
distributor.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with President Bill Clinton last month, leading
executives of the TV industry promised to create a system to work
along with the so-called v-chip, which is required by the
Telecommunications Act.
</P>
<P>
The v-chip can recognize sexual and violent content in a TV
program. With a remote control device, parents would be able to
block individual shows or whole categories of programs.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the MPAA, members of the group include
representatives of ABC, CBS, NBC, Fox, United Paramount, the
National Cable Television Association, the National Association of
Broadcasters, public television and independent television
stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
