<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 05:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multimillionaire Forbes Quits Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. multimillionaire magazine
publisher Steve Forbes has decided to quit race for the Republican
presidential nomination and throw his support to U.S. Senate
Republican Leader Bob Dole, his aides said today.
</P>
<P>
Forbes, who had spent some 30 million U.S. dollars since he
announced his participation in the campaign last September, made
the decision one day after Dole swept the Republican primaries in
seven states on so-called "Super Tuesday."
</P>
<P>
Forbes campaign manager Bill Dal Col told reporters that Forbes
himself will make the retreat announcement sometime on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the publisher earned 901,000 votes during the primary
season--some 16 percent of those cast, putting him third behind
Dole and conservative TV commentator Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
The 72-year-old Senate majority leader Dole has won more than
700 delegates to the Republican National Convention. A total of
996 delegates are required to get the nomination for the White
House candidate at the party convention to be held in San Diego in
August.
</P>
<P>
Buchanan is distant second with less than 8O delegates.
</P>
<P>
It is almost certain that Dole, widely supported by Republican
mainstream and dozens of GOP state governors, will win the party
nomination.
</P>
<P>
Dole has held out to Buchanan and Forbes and urged them to
unite behind him to fight Democratic President Bill Clinton in
elections on November 5.
</P>
<P>
Forbes bowed to inevitability of Dole victory, but Buchanan has
rejected Dole's call and vowed to battle with the GOP presidential
front-runner to San Diego. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
