<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 05:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Yeltsin Under Pressure to Sack Grachev  (by Zhang Tiegang) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 14 (Xinhua) -- To sack or not to sack has become
a major dilemma for Boris Yeltsin as the countdown begins to the
June 16 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The dismissal of Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has developed
into an important test for the Russian president who is facing
increasing pressure from supporters to get rid of one of his most
loyal political allies.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's advisers are telling him that he cannot win the
presidential election with the ball and chain of Grachev and the
Chechen war around his neck.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, First Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Soskovets, who
runs Yeltsin's re-election headquarters, told reporters a
substantial number of presidential campaigners are actively
pushing the president to fire the 48-year-old minister.
</P>
<P>
Grachev, one of Yeltsin's most loyal political allies, is
blamed for letting the 15-month war in the separatist republic of
Chechnya drag on.
</P>
<P>
Soskovets said that the campaign in Chechnya, along with its
mistakes and setbacks, is the "heaviest burden" Yeltsin has to
bear in his re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
Presidential advisers are urging Yeltsin to name those guilty
of "bad planning" in the Chechen operation, pointing their finger
at Grachev, who once vowed to quell separatism in Chechnya's
capital Grozny within two hours with just two airborne regiments.
</P>
<P>
It turned out that entire divisions of Russian servicemen
ended up fighting in the rebellious city and republic in a war of
attrition which has already claimed more than 30,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
And last Thursday, Chechen militants loyal to separatist leader
Dzhokhar Dudayev went close to recapturing several parts of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Rumors of Grachev's fall from grace have been bubbling for
months in Moscow, amid allegations of corruption, incompetence and
a series of political gaffes.
</P>
<P>
A poll by the All-Russian Center for Public Opinion Studies
found that both radical and moderate democrats, represented by
Yegor Gaidar's Russia's Democratic Choice and Grigory Yavlinsky's
Yabloko bloc respectively, dislike Grachev.
</P>
<P>
Both have urged Yeltsin to sack Grachev and Yeltsin needs their
support to defeat Communist Party chief Zyuganov in the election
race.
</P>
<P>
Even the communists and other opposition forces dislike
Grachev, who, when police left Moscow unprotected in October 1993,
ordered the military to storm the White House to prevent an
attempted coup, according to local press.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Grachev has survived widespread criticism has
been attributed to his personal loyalty to the president.
</P>
<P>
"This loyalty has always been Grachev's strongest card," the
Moscow Tribune said, and "Yeltsin has always been able to depend
on him."
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency said Yeltsin would be deciding
Grachev's fate in the coming days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
