<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 05:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French, German Response to Middle East Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac and
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl both hailed Wednesday's
international anti-terrorist "Summit of the Peacemakers" in Egypt
as a success.
</P>
<P>
Chirac told reporters today that the meeting of the peacemakers
is in itself progress in the peace process after the force of
hatred gained the upper hand for a while.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to provide Palestine
with more aid and investment to improve living conditions. Only
when better living conditions are in sight can peace take root in
the hearts of the people, he said.
</P>
<P>
The French president also hoped the Syrian-Israeli and
Lebanese-Israeli peace negotiations will yield positive results as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl described as "remarkable" the
four-hour summit in the Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh which
was attended by 27 nations.
</P>
<P>
Kohl said failure of the Middle East peace process would cause
panic among moderate Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The Moslem militant group Hamas's terrorist activities have
struck terror not only in Israel but also in other Middle East
countries, said Kohl, and the meeting has assured those countries
that the international community will support their fight against
the opponents of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The German Chancellor also praised the summit for avoiding the
contentious issue of whether to point a finger at certain
countries as "sponsors of terrorism".
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the European Union's relations with Iran, the
French President said the EU holds different views from the United
States, while Kohl said the U.S. has expressed its understanding
of the EU's attitude towards Iran.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders said the EU will continue to hold critical talks
with Iran, which has been accused by the U.S. of supporting
terrorists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
