<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continental Free Trade Zone Talks to Be Resumed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Trade ministers from
the 34 countries on the American continent will resume talks on
the establishment of a continental free trade zone on March 18-21.
</P>
<P>
The participants at the meeting in Colombia are expected to
sign a document on the progress of the negotiations, said Jose
Botafogo, the Brazilian undersecretary of integration, economic
and foreign trade matters.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four American countries pledged at the Summit of the
Americas held in Miami in December 1994 to establish a free trade
zone in the hemisphere by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The United States wants all the countries on the continent to
take part in the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA),
reached between the U.S., Mexico and Canada in 1992, according to
Botafogo.
</P>
<P>
However, MERCOSUR, made up of Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and
Uruguay, the largest American trade bloc after NAFTA, believes
that the U.S. position does not take into account the individual
advantages of other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
