<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 04:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America Employs Millions of Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Millions of children in Latin
America and the Caribbean, instead of going to school, are
employed as child laborers, a U.N. report shows.
</P>
<P>
There are between 16-18 million child laborers in Latin America
and the Caribbean and on average, a third do not go to school, a
joint study by the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) and the
U.N. Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean
(CEPAL).
</P>
<P>
Children who work lose two or more years of schooling and as a
result earn some 20 percent less than adults, the report says.
</P>
<P>
Overall, 17 percent of children in the region work and in some
countries the number rises to 32 percent, a figure described as
"worrisome" by UNICEF Regional Director Marta Mauras here today.
</P>
<P>
She condemned child labor as perpetuating poverty, and while she
admitted that it was sometimes a way of lifting some households
out of extreme poverty, its overall impact on the reduction of
poverty was almost zero.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNICEF-CEPAL investigation, child labor is
concentrated in unskilled jobs and is heavily exploited.
</P>
<P>
The report calls for programs to subsidize poor households with
children to improve education conditions of the working
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 04:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Move Hurts, But Not Stems Investments in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The enacted U.S. Helms-Burton
Bill imposing sanctions on Cuba's trade partners and investors
could hurt, but not stem the influx of foreign money into the country,
a senior Cuban official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister for Foreign Investment and Economic Aid
Raul Taladrid said the U.S. anti-Cuban bill, which was ratified
yesterday by President Bill Clinton, has drawn strong worldwide
condemnations, including that from the Rio Group, a political
consultative body comprising 12 Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
The group announced today "its most vigorous rejection" of the
U.S. move that "violates the principles of international law, the
charters of the United Nations and the Organization of American
States."
</P>
<P>
Taladrid added that Cuba is negotiating with more countries on
protection of foreign investments, though since 1993, 15
nations have already signed agreements with Cuba on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Last year, he added, Cuba had received more than 2
billion U.S. dollars from 55 countries, and now another 200 business
negotiations are underway.
</P>
<P>
According to other reports from Montevideo, the Uruguayan
government expressed in a press bulletin that it will adhere to
the position of the Rio Group, which rejects the U.S. bill to
sanction those who invest or negotiate with Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
