<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 04:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke031317--German Paedophile Gets 43 Years' Jail Term in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A German man has been sentenced
to 43 years' imprisonment on a series of charges of child sexual
abuse and intended trafficking in pornography.
</P>
<P>
The sentence, passed on Wednesday by a Thon Buri criminal court
on Bernd Karl-Heinz Nierenz, 36, is the heaviest handed down to a
foreigner for sexual offenses against children in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In December 1994, police raided Nierenz's flat in Thon Buri,
Bangkok, and found 136 photo albums filled with pornographic
pictures of underage boys, 29 pornographic videotapes, more than
100 roles of pornographic film negatives, and advertising
brochures for pornographic materials and child sex tours in
Thailand, intended for sale or public distribution.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Denies Jones, 47, a British-Guyanan national, was
sentenced to a 50-year term in prison for similar offenses, but he
was sentenced in two separate trials.
</P>
<P>
Nierenz's conviction came in the face of a six-month-old
campaign waged on the Internet targeting Thailand as a center of
child prostitution and trafficking and encouraging people to
boycott Thai products.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, some developed countries have accepted that
they should share the responsibility for child prostitution in
developing countries and have enacted extraterritorial laws that
enable them to prosecute their own nationals for crimes committed
against children abroad.
</P>
<P>
Although there have been a few convictions under these
extraterritorial laws in countries like Sweden and Germany, such
cases remain difficult to prosecute due to complicated
cross-national legal procedures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
