<HEADLINE> Thailand Makes Bid to Save Thais from Hanging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Thai House Committee on Labor
and Social Welfare has made an eleventh-hour bid to save five Thai
workers due to be hanged in Singapore Friday.
</P>
<P>
The panel has decided to request the Singaporean parliament
president to postpone the execution.
</P>
<P>
The committee has urged Thai House Speaker Boon-eua
Prasertsuwan to submit a request to the Singaporean parliament
president to help push for a lesser punishment or at least
postpone the hanging.
</P>
<P>
Five Thai workers in Singapore face death sentence after they
were found guilty of robbery and murder of two Indian nationals in
September 1993. They are now in Changi prison, Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The panel hopes that Singapore would delay the execution and
commute the death sentence to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The Thai House Justice and Human Rights Committee also urged
Prime Minister Banharn Silpa-Archa to ask his Singaporean
counterpart Goh Chok Tong to pardon the workers. Goh is said to
be the only person with the authority to suspend the punishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
