<HEADLINE> Nepali Ruling Partner Leaders Differ on Opposition  Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the National
Democratic Party (RPP), second ruling party and a key force under
the current political situation in Nepal, Wednesday differed over
the party's stance on a no-confidence motion against the present
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of RPP parliamentary party held late Wednesday
decided to let parliamentary party leader Lokendra Bahadur Chand
to finalize whether RPP would support the no-confidence motion
against the government to be tabled by the main opposition
Communist Party of Nepal (UML) in the parliament next week.
</P>
<P>
The UML party has offered RPP to form an alternative coalition
government with Chand as prime minister if the no-confidence
motion is passed in the forthcoming special House session slated
for March 20, reports said.
</P>
<P>
With 19 seats in the House of Representatives, RPP holds the
key to survival of the present three-party government under Sher
Bahadur Deuba. NML and the main ruling Nepali Congress (NC) party
have 88 and 86 seats respectively in the 205-seat House.
</P>
<P>
Two RPP leaders, Foreign Minister Prakash Chandra Lohani and
Water Resources Minister Pashupati J.B. Rana of the present
government, openly opposed to form an alliance with the UML party
and walked out of the RPP meeting Wednesday to show their
opposition. Seven other RPP MPs were absent from the Wednesday
parliamentary party meeting, it was reported.
</P>
<P>
It was expected a RPP Central Working Committee meeting would
be held soon to take up the matter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
