<HEADLINE> Thailand Not to Be Used as Base to Attack 3rd Nation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Ministry spokesman
Surapong Jayanama has reiterated that Thailand has a clear policy
of not permitting any foreign organization to use it as a base to
assail a third country.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand offers freedom of expression for everybody, but it is
against any foreign group using its territory as a base for
attacking a third country," said Surapong, who is director-general
of the Information Department.
</P>
<P>
He made the comment when asked why Thai police Wednesday
briefly detained two Amnesty International activists and seized
from them 50 copies of a report attacking China on human rights
issues.
</P>
<P>
Suvidhya Simaskul, director-general of the Foreign Ministry's
East Asia Department, also asked, "why should they use Thailand to
attack a third country? it's not done anywhere in the world."
</P>
<P>
A Thai police officer told the Amnesty International detainees
that using Thailand to launch attacks on China was not good for
Thailand's international image.  
</P>
