<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Farmer's Legendary Tale on Ecological Farming (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- It was a real tough job to get
someone suitable to head Xiaozhangzhuang village -- because all
grown-ups in the village then went begging away from their homes,
and the township government had to call in a young farmer from a
nearby village, Zhang Jiashun, to fill the vacancy.
</P>
<P>
This happened 34 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Today, all of my 2,000-strong villagers have all thrown away
their beggar's bowls," said Zhang, who is here attending this
year's session of the National People's Congress, China's
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's village, Xiaozhangzhuang of east China's Anhui
Province, is on the north side of the Huaihe River that used to
be a leading scourge in the region with frequent flooding.
</P>
<P>
Zhang told Xinhua that the majority of his fellow farmers have
moved out of tidy straw-thatched cottages and to rows of
reinforce-concrete houses, and a modern, tree-covered town has
sprung up on former barren sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
The per-capita income of villagers reached 2,400 yuan (about
300 US dollars) last year, approaching or reaching the standard
set by the Chinese government for a relatively comfortable life,
according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said that his fellow villagers, like their urban
cousins, now have access to drinking water.
</P>
<P>
For all what he has contributed to his village, Zhang and his
village have been honored with two gold prizes by the United
Nations Environment Program, one for himself and the other,
"Global 500," for his village that "has established a growth
pattern for ecological agriculture, which is of great value in
reference to rural areas of poorer countries."
</P>
<P>
Born into a poor famer's family, Zhang, 58, does not have any
schooling, and even to date he can hardly read or write.
</P>
<P>
"I dispatched 200 of my men to collect droppings before we
grew wheat and sesame," he said, referring to the first thing
he did after he was named head of his village.
</P>
<P>
"Then I traveled four consecutive days and nights by train to
Tianshan Mountain pasture area in the northwestern Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region and bought back 40 horses with the money from
our sales of wheat and sesame," Zhang recalled.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 30-strong years, Zhang has led his men to
deep-plough their 360 ha of farmland, dig 20 kg of tunnels and 15
fish pools, sink 64 wells and rebuild a forest belt of 50 kg long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 03:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Thai PM's Arrest Ordered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Criminal Court has
ordered to arrest a former member of parliament for failing to
show up to hear a court verdict on him.
</P>
<P>
Seksan Saenphum, ex-member of parliament from the Chart Thai
(Thai Nation) Party, was in contravention of a court order as he
failed to appear to hear the appeal court ruling on him.
</P>
<P>
The Criminal Court sentenced Seksan to six months in jail on
March 26 last year after finding him guilty of defaming Major
General Sornchai Montriwat, who was a secretary to the then
interior minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh.
</P>
<P>
The Appeal Court Wednesday was ready to announce the reduction
of his sentence to a two-year suspended jail term after Seksan
filed an appeal with it.
</P>
<P>
Major General Sornchai, who currently is a deputy interior
minister, filed a defamation suit against Seksan with the Criminal
Court after a censure debate on November 11, 1993 during which
Seksan accused him of smuggling heroin into the United States.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit currently is a deputy prime minister and defense
minister of the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
