<HEADLINE> Households Buy 220,000 Computers in China in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Computer are on the verge of
becoming a new family necessity as common as the color television,
washing machine and refrigerator in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese families purchased some 220,000 personal computers last
year, accounting for 20 per cent of the PC sales in the country,
according to the national newspaper People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
Prodded by the rapid development of the information industry,
household demand for PCs rose sharply in urban areas. Statistics
show that about five percent of families of Shanghai, China's
largest city, have bought computers, and the number is expected to
be 20 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that when 10 percent of households are equipped
with computers, the pressure to buy will become stronger in other
families, and PC sales will really take off.
</P>
<P>
Expanded applications of PCs have also given a new push to the
computer stampede, now that education, office, and entertainment
software are widely available to families here.
</P>
<P>
To cater to the rising demands, more domestic brands will begin
to appear in the next few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
