<HEADLINE> IRRI Chief Studies Paddy Cultivation in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Director-General of the
International Rice Research Institute (IRRI) based in the
Philippines George Rothschild is currently here on a study tour
of summer paddy cultivation in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Paddy is the main crop of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The study also covers integrated farming in Ayeyawaddy and
Mandalay divisions, research farms and some agricultural research
centers in Yezin and Pyinmana, central Myanmar, according to
today's "The New Light of Myanmar".
</P>
<P>
The visit of the IRRI chief is also aimed at signing of a
cooperation agreement between the IRRI and the Myanmar Ministry of
Agriculture on tasks in agriculture during the five-year plan
period.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister for Agriculture Lieutenant General Myint Aung
met the IRRI chief on Wednesday night and discussed with him
boosting of paddy production in Myanmar, production of quality and
high yield species, opening courses on development of cultivation
techniques, acquiring efficient technicians and securing technical
assistance, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official statistics, the paddy yield in
Myanmar was recorded at 901 million baskets (over 18 million tons)
and rice export reached up to over 1 million tons in the 1994-95
fiscal year. Myanmar is planning to export 1.5 million tons of
rice in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The IRRI chief arrived here Wednesday at the invitation of
Myanmar Minister for Agriculture Lieutenant General Myint Aung.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 03:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Aims to Rebuild Competitiveness in Sea shipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sea shipping plays a crucial role in the European Union's
economy, with 90 per cent of foreign trade and 30 per cent of
inter-EC trade conducted by sea transport, the European Commission
said.
</P>
<P>
With the shipping industry facing increasing globalization, the
Commission called for the redefining of international competition
rules to ensure fair competition, efficiency and security in sea
transportation and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
It also called for measures to expand the EU's shipping fleet,
improve coordination among member states on registration and to
encourage short-haul transport.
</P>
<P>
The Commission also urged the EU to boost cooperation with
Mediterranean countries.
</P>
<P>
In its new strategy papers, the EC proposed great efforts be
made in the following three areas in order to increase EU'S
competitiveness in sea transportation.
</P>
<P>
* to promote professional training and strengthen protection of
the sea transportation-related jobs.
</P>
<P>
* to strengthen and coordinate development research on sea
transportation and the whole shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
* to re-define the EU's national aid policy on sea
transportation in order to coordinate the different systems in
member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 03:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Urges to Eliminate Xenophobia Against Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Mexico today appealed to
Central and North American countries to abandon their xenophobic
approach toward immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Foreign Minister Jose Angel Gurria Trevino urged the 10
countries taking part in the first regional conference on
migration to respect the human rights of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
He said that close to 100 million migrant laborers are working
throughout the world and that no country or region can remain
immune from this global phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican minister told the meeting that economic and social
development is the most effective long-term solution to the
migration issue.
</P>
<P>
The most urgent task, he said, is to explore and implement a
mechanism to benefit both the countries of origin and destination
of the immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"We have to collaborate to find answers that will enable us to
reconcile a modern administration of borders that will facilitate
the free passage of goods and services in accordance with the
priorities of each nation," Trevino said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, which drew participants from Canada, the
United States, Mexico, Belize, Guatemala, Honduras, El Salvador,
Costa Rica, Nicaragua and Panama, opened here today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
