<HEADLINE> Argentina Criticizes British Military Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Argentine deputy foreign
minister Fernando Petrella today criticized British military
presence around the Georgia Island in the South Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
He said that the British military presence was unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
In statements to the local press, the deputy foreign minister
said that if Britain "has proper rights" over the Georgia Island
"it would not need a military presence."
</P>
<P>
However, he confirmed that the British authorities have
refunded to the Argentine fishing boat "Antarctic III", which works
for a U.S. food processing company, 10,000 U.S. dollars in tax and
returned the boat to its owner.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine government assumed the move a sign that London is
relaxing its attitude in face of the conflict over the island,
though the press here reported that Britain has added a
surveillance plane and a nuclear-powered submarine to its warships
patroling the area around it. 
</P>
