<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 125 Year-Old Former Brazilian Slave Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- One of the two oldest Brazilian
slaves died on Tuesday just two months before her 126th birthday
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Elizaria Damiana Fonseca, died after a short illness at the old
people's home she had been living in for the last 40 years in
Jiundai just outside Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
The former slave, who until recently could still sew and look
after other residents, never competed "officially" with her fellow
countrywoman, Maria Do Carmo, for the title of oldest woman in the
world since she did not have a birth certificate to prove her
birth in 1870, though several people appealed to the editors of
the Guinness Book of Records.
</P>
<P>
According to the nuns who cared for her, she would have turned
126 on May 11 while Do Carmo had her 125th birthday three weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
Damiana was snatched away by a Portuguese adventurer before he
returned to Europe and she remembered many of her relatives and
friends were abused in the era of slavery which was abolished in
1888.
</P>
<P>
During that era she worked on several haciendas in the south
eastern part of the country until old age forced her to enter an
asylum in Jiundai run by a religious community.
</P>
<P>
She said that the secret of her longevity was not smoking,
eating lots of pasta and drinking "pinga" (liquor). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0265 </DOCNO>
