<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Spur Growth of Chinese-style Fast food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) --The Ministry of Internal Trade
(MIT) will soon issue guidelines aimed at boosting the growth of
Chinese-style fast food and improving the profile of this
burgeoning sector.
</P>
<P>
The first national development plan for fast food production
and services, expected to be approved by the State Council in the
near future, is "a measure of profound significance " to the
industry, "China Daily" said, quoting Ling Dawei, director of
the Catering and Service Department under the MIT.
</P>
<P>
The plan will enhance the industrialization and standardization
of fast food production and chain-stores, which are already
booming in cities, prompted by an improvement of people's living
standards, and the influx of foreign fast food.
</P>
<P>
Fast food services in China have grown rapidly in recent years,
but problems also exist, Ling said.
</P>
<P>
The domestic fast food sector is "lagging " behind market
demand and suffers from a lack of convenience, nutrition, variety
and hygiene, as well as well-known brands that can compete with
foreign names, he added.
</P>
<P>
As part of its major tasks in 1996, Ling said, the MIT is to
help the sector catch up with the pace of national economic
development and cope with the changes in household affairs.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 million yuan (1.2 million US dollars) will be
earmarked for the purpose this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
China's fast food sector grew 20 percent in 1995. 
