<HEADLINE> Moldova Sticks to One-China Policy, Says Moldovan Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A high-level Moldovan Diplomat
said today his country regards Beijing as the sole legitimate
government of China with Taiwan an inalienable part of China.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Xinhua, Vladimir Gusnir, a
ministerial level counsellor of Moldova's proposed embassy in
China, said that since the establishment of diplomatic ties with
China in 1992, the two countries have enjoyed a good relations and
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Moldova, which neighbours the Ukraine and Romania, has signed
a series of agreements and protocols with China to further
strengthen cooperation in politics, trade and economy, culture,
and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Gusnir will leave for Beijing on March 16 to set up an embassy
in the Chinese capital, Moldova's only embassy in Asia. He said
his main priority in Beijing is to try to push the friendly,
cooperative relations between the two countries to a new high.
</P>
<P>
Moldova, a country of 33,700 square kilometers and just over 4
million people, declared its independence from the former Soviet
Union in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
