<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baiheliang Underwater Yangtze River Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Preparations have begun for
work on China's largest underwater museum at Baiheliang (White
Crane Ridge), in Fuling city of southwest China's Sichuan
Province, local official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The 1,600-meter-long, 15-meter-wide rock ridge is in the
Yangtze River to the north of Fuling. It was given the name
because of the white cranes that used to gather on it in ancient
times. A stone carving from the Tang Dynasty (618-907) can be seen
on the rocky ground when it appears in the dry season.
</P>
<P>
The carving has 18 fish carvings which were used for measuring
water levels. Descriptions about changes in the water level were
also carved, providing some of the earliest hydrology measuring
devices in the world.
</P>
<P>
Carvings of famous Chinese calligraphers from the past are
preserved on the rock, which is also called as "Forest of
Underwater Steles".
</P>
<P>
Baiheliang will be covered by 175 meters deep of water because
of the Three Gorges Project, and the Chinese government has
decided to spend some 100 million yuan on an underwater museum.
</P>
<P>
A 30 or 40-meter-high spheroid will cover 220 m. of the stone,
anchored to the river bed, forming an underwater museum.
</P>
<P>
The museum will have two exhibition rooms, showing not only the
stone carvings but also landscapes along the Yangtze River valley,
with objects, pictures, and films.
</P>
<P>
A 100-meter-long underwater passageway will connect the museum
to the river bank. The whole project is to be completed in ten
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
