<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Calls for European Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe
today called for the creation of a European army of between
250,000 and 300,000.
</P>
<P>
"Five great countries" of the European Union -- Britain,
France, Germany, Italy and Spain, could each send between 50,000
and 60,000 troops, Juppe told a Paris conference of leaders of the
European Democratic Union, a group of conservative and Christian
Democrat Parties with 24 seats in the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The force would come under the leadership of the Western
European Union, a 10-nation military body set up in 1954 to
discuss defense issues, and should be able to operate autonomously
or in coordination with U.S. forces within NATO.
</P>
<P>
Juppe said it was high time the European Union (EU) took
concrete steps to build up joint defense and the means necessary
for joint intervention, with or without the Americans.
</P>
<P>
France has backed joint European defence initiatives and a
"concerted" nuclear deterrent since last autumn but has so far had
little support from other EU members. The country has also moved
closer towards NATO military institutions, although there has been
no suggestion of joining.
</P>
<P>
President Jacques Chirac unveiled a reform of the French armed
forces last month, anticipating a streamlined, more professional
and mobile force by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
However, Chirac said that the participation in Eurocorps, a
European force grouping Belgium, Germany, Luxembourg, Spain and
France, would not be affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
