<HEADLINE> Thai Prime Minister to Visit Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Banharn
Silpa-Archa will pay an official visit to Myanmar from Sunday at
the invitation of Chairman of the Myanmar State Law and Order
Restoration Council and Prime Minister Senior General Than Shwe,
it was officially announced here today.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time ever for a prime minister of Thailand
to visit this neighboring country in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Banharn met Than Shwe last December at the 5th ASEAN summit in
Bangkok where Than Shwe attended the meeting of ASEAN leaders and
leaders of the three nations -- Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's relations with Thailand have been strained since
early last year due to some border incidents which led to
Myanmar's closure of the three border checkpoints at
Tachilek-Maesai, Myawaddy-Maesod and Kawthaung-Ranong.
</P>
<P>
In late 1995, Myanmar Deputy Prime Minister Vice-Admiral Maung
Maung Khin and Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Defense Minister
General Chavalit Yongchaiyudh exchanged visits and finally reached
a border trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
During Banharn's forthcoming visit to Myanmar, the border trade
agreement between the two countries is expected to be formally
signed.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, Thailand's
investment in Myanmar amounted to 421.12 million US dollars in 29
related projects by November 1995, ranking the fourth after the
United Kingdom, Singapore and France.  
</P>
