<HEADLINE> Germany Calls For Controls On Cigarette, Alcohol, Drug Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- German experts have called for
tighter control over cigarette, alcohol and drug advertisements to
improve the social environment children grow up in.
</P>
<P>
They also called for a levy of five percent of the 1.6 billion
marks spent on advertising in Germany each year to be spent on
anti-drugs programs in schools.
</P>
<P>
The experts made the appeal at the first European conference on
children, youth and drugs, which opened Tuesday in Munster,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by German agencies, some 15 percent of 14
year olds are addicted to smoking, with some having started
smoking when they were eight. An even greater percentage of
teenagers are addicted to alcohol.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of teenagers who regularly take
pain-killing, hypnotic, sedative and other narcotic drugs is on
the increase. For example, nearly 40 percent of 12-years-olds
often take pain-killers.
</P>
<P>
Experts blamed rising consumption on advertising, which costs
about 1.6 billion marks (1.1 billion U.S. dollars) every year.
</P>
<P>
They suggested five percent of the money be levied to carry out
an anti-drugs program in kindergartens and schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
