<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Planting More Trees to Fight Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Forestry departments in east
China's Zhejiang Province have chosen a number of tree species to
be used as natural fire-prevention belts.
</P>
<P>
The province has started building a 30,000-km natural
fire-prevention forest belt, according to Cheng Weishan, head of
the provincial forest industry department.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, trees have been felled and ditches dug to fight
fires, but the results are often damage to vegetation and soil
loss.
</P>
<P>
After a number of experiments were conducted in the past years,
forest researchers in Zhejiang found that several species of
trees, including bayberry, have low burning points and can be
used as natural prevention shelter belts.
</P>
<P>
The shelter belt may completely replace traditional fire
shelters, scientists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
