<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A major American software
developer and supplier signed a 3.5 million-US-dollar deal with a
Chinese company on Wednesday, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The contract was inked in Beijing by the Oracle Co. and the
Shenzhen-based Rayes Technology Group. The contract is the largest
of its kind for the US company since it entered the Chinese market
in 1989, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Rayes President Lu Ruifeng said his company will use
Oracle-supplied software to build China Online, a computer
information network that aims to connect 26 cities within six
months and have 20,000 users.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of China Online is to use existing computers and
telecommunication technology to promote development of information
services.
</P>
<P>
Work units and individuals can use the network to contact
services about banking, chain stores, securities, futures,
taxation and electronic mail, according to Oracle.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government encourages information services in order
to promote the flow of information and its use in economic
development. 
