<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Loans to help China's Petrochemical Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Export and Import Bank of
Japan will loan 98.94 billion yen (about 773 million US dollars)
to finance China's key state projects, including several
petrochemical undertakings in Henan, Hubei and Jiangsu provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, re-loaned by Bank of China
(BOC), the long-term preferential loans are the third batch this
year signed between BOC and the Export and Import Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The first two batches in January and February, which totalled
about 1.58 billion US dollars, went to support projects such as
the Feilaixia Hydropower Station in Guangdong Province and the
Xiangtan Chemical Fiber Plant in Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The loans are part of the Japanese government's foreign
assistance to developing countries. The Export and Import Bank of
Japan, one of the government's financial institutions, has been
asked to grant part of the assistance.
</P>
<P>
These long-term preferential loans have fewer limitations on
the sectors in which they can be used, and there are also fewer
restrictions on the countries and regions from which equipment and
materials can be brought from, making the loans easier to use, BOC
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
