<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compulsory Education Popular in Guizhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou
Province, which used to have a high rate of illiteracy, has
extended the nine-year compulsory education to 73 of its 86
counties, and more than 95 percent of the young people in some 30
counties are now literate.
</P>
<P>
For a long time, the mountainous province, which is inhabited
by many ethnic groups, lagged far behind other provinces and
regions in cultural and educational development.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has made eliminating illiteracy its
main goal and has vowed to wipe out illiteracy in the province by
the year 2000 and bring compulsory education to 95 percent of its
population.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that another 310,000 young people became
literate in the province last year, bringing its illiteracy rate
down nearly 2 percentage points to the current 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
With the popularization of compulsory education, education has
seen faster growth, and some 96 percent of the school-age children
are now able to go to school in the province.
</P>
<P>
In addition, enrollments in higher education and in secondary
schools in the province have risen 4.2 and 20.5 percent,
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
