<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls for Better Coordination in Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has urged Russian foreign policy makers to coordinate and remove
differences of views in their work, a high-ranking diplomat said
at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Igor Ivanov, first deputy foreign minister, told the conference
that Yeltsin signed a decree Tuesday ordering foreign ministry
officials to be more efficient in their work.
</P>
<P>
According to Ivanov, the decree stipulates that only the
president, prime minister and foreign minister are entitled to
make initiative statements on the country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Presidential and foreign ministry spokesmen can make policy
announcements whereas departments of other ministries can do it
only when authorized by the foreign ministry, and make comment
when instructed.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Yeltsin criticized former Foreign Minister
Andrei Kozyrev for failing to coordinate with other government
departments.
</P>
<P>
"Anonymous spokesmen for the foreign ministry cannot be
considered official," Ivanov told the press.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is to demonstrate Russia's positions
with the utmost exactness," he noted.
</P>
<P>
All bodies of power in Russia and of the Russian Federation
should inform the foreign ministry of their foreign affairs
maneuvers and coordinate with the ministry, Ivanov quoted the
decree.
</P>
<P>
"The more order there is in Russian foreign policy, the more
effective it will be," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
He said that violator of the decree will be reported to the
president and the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Switch to Increase Speed of China's Trains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- China's railway department has
succeeded in developing a new railway switch that can remarkably
improve the speed of trains.
</P>
<P>
The new switch allows trains to travel as fast as 160 km per
hour. The present speed of Chinese trains is 60 to 80 kmh. The
lifespan of the switch is also twice that of the ones in common
use on the Chinese railway lines.
</P>
<P>
The switch was developed jointly by several research
institutions of the Ministry of Railways and manufactured by the
Baoji Bridge Plant in Shaanxi Province, in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the new switch is as technologically advanced
as those used elsewhere in the world in the 1990s and is of
critical importance to the department's plan to boost the speed
of trains on China's major railway lines in the next five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
