<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Government Backs Stockholm's Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 13 (Xinhua/OANA) -- The Swedish government
will guarantee Stockholm's bid for the 2004 summer Olympic Games,
its civil affairs minister said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The government decided at noon today it will give a 2.5
billion-crown (368.1 million U.S. dollars) guarantee," Minister
Marita Ulvskog told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The government said it would raise the money by arranging a
state lottery.
</P>
<P>
Stockholm city mayor Mats Hulth told the reporters the budget
for the Olympic Games could be 11.8 billion crowns (1.74 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The cost could be covered by issuing the state lottery, selling
television licences and contract sponsors.
</P>
<P>
Stockholm, which decided to enter the bidding race last
October, will submit its formal bid to the International Olympic
Committee (IOC) in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
