<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Concern over New Petrol on Rise in NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Concern is on the rise in New
Zealand over the safety of a new unleaded petrol introduced to
replace the old super leaded fuel.
</P>
<P>
Some government agencies are now joining forces to deal with
the concern, since the first complaint about the new fuel surfaced
last Thursday. So far there have been over 280 complaints,
including a few car fires.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Health, Environment and Commerce ministries,
the Civil Aviation Authority and Occupational Safety and Health
department met with representatives of the oil companies this
morning to voice their concern over the safety issue. This is the
first time the government agencies have taken a coordinated
approach.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, Prime Minister Jim Bolger and Energy
Minister Duog Kidd also met with oil companies representatives to
hear their explanation about the problem, which they have failed
to provide. However, they said the new fuel is safe.
</P>
<P>
On one point, Bolger even said motorists should stop using the
petrol if the oil companies cannot give assurance that it is safe.
</P>
<P>
The new petrol, known as 96 octane, uses aromatic hydrocarbons
to replace lead as the catalyst in an effort to reduce pollution.
However, the introduction of the lead-free petrol has thrown the
companies into a public relations nightmare.
</P>
<P>
The companies said it is now impossible to stop selling the new
petrol on the market, since they stopped making the leaded super
last December to meet the government's policy of a lead-free
petrol supply by 1996.
</P>
<P>
But many New Zealanders said they do not want to see one poison
being replaced by another poison.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, the oil companies are carrying out research on
what is wrong with the new fuel, which damages rubber parts of
some vehicles. They said such problems have not been reported in
other countries using the same fuel.
</P>
<P>
Although uncertain about the cause of the problem, the
companies have decided to reduce the level of aromatics in 96
octane.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, drivers of fuel tanks said they want an independent
body to be involved in safety of the new fuel. The demand came
after some drivers reported headaches and nausea after exposed to
fumes from the new petrol.
</P>
<P>
They have threatened to take industrial actions if the problem
is not solved.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
