<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Police Arrest Criminals in Ilidza for Looting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 13 (Xinhua) -- NATO and U.N. representatives
said today that gangs arriving from Sarajevo were looting houses
and terrorizing Serbs remaining in Ilidza, a Serb suburb which was
transfered to the Muslim-Croat federation on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
International Police Force Commissioner Peter Fitzgerald told
reporters that federation police arrested several persons today
who were looting houses.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Serbs to remain in Ilidza, although he could
give them no guarantees. Ilidza was the fourth of five Serb-held
suburb in Sarajevo which must be handed to Muslim-Croat federation
control. The last Serb district Grbavica will be transferred on
March 19.
</P>
<P>
"All I can say is that the international police force will be
present in considerable numbers" in Ilidza, Tanjug quoted
Fitzgerald as saying.
</P>
<P>
Less than 2,000 Serbs now remain in Ilidza which had a
population of about 25,000 before the Dayton peace accord was
signed last December. All the others had left before the sector
was taken control by 90 federation police Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fitzgerald said that 90 police were probably not enough to
resolve the present situation in Ilidza, adding he would discuss
this with the Sarajevo government Internal Affairs Minister Avdo
Hebib.
</P>
<P>
He warned that situation could become very dangerous unless
terrorism was stopped quickly in the sector.
</P>
<P>
International police representatives have received many
complaints on cars stealing and house looting and on two separate
attacks on a man and a woman in Ilidza, Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
The international community High Representative for civilian
affairs in Bosnia Carl Bildt requested today in Brussels a direct
IFOR participation in civilian police activities in Sarajevo
districts which were placed under federation authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
