<HEADLINE> Inspection of Heavy Arms Begins in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 13 (Xinhua) -- An international team of experts
has begun inspection of military arsenals of the former warring
sides in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The inspection will show the size of the heavy arms arsenals of
the Bosnian Croats, Muslims and Serbs, which, under the Dayton
agreement, should ultimately be reduced, according to a statement
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
issued today.
</P>
<P>
The first team of inspectors, which included four
representatives of the Bosnian Serb state, began the inspection of
the military arsenal of the Muslim-Croat federation.
</P>
<P>
Another team with four Muslim-Croat representatives has left
for the Republika Srpska for the arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50 inspections is planned to be carried out in 50
days, Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The work is expected to complete before June 6, when talks on a
general disarmament agreement are expected to end in Vienna. The
agreement is planned to be signed by June 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
