<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-13 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fed Report Shows Economy Regaining Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy appears to be
regaining its footing with a number of encouraging signs of
increased activity, the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) said here
today.
</P>
<P>
In its latest nationwide survey, the Fed said that most of its
12 regional banks reported moderate to solid gains in economic
activity in recent weeks. Many credited the pickup to rebounds
from weather-related slowdowns earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
It said that pickup in economic activity was occurring without
an increase in inflationary pressures. Most districts reported an
"encouraging pick-up in February" in retail sales except areas in
the West and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
"Wages and price pressure are generally described as subdued,
notwithstanding observations of tight labour markets in several
districts," the Fed said.
</P>
<P>
The new Fed survey, known as the beige book, will be used by
the Fed when its Federal Open Market Committee will consider
interest rates in the next meeting on March 26.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said the generally upbeat Fed survey, coming
after last Friday's report of the biggest jump in payroll jobs in
more than a decade, strengthened their belief that the Fed will
not cut rates further.
</P>
<P>
But others said that February's employment report, which
resulted in a big drop at the Wall Street stock and bond market
last Friday, was more of a fluke than an indicator of an
overheating economy and further drop of interest rate was
possible.
</P>
<P>
The Fed cut interest rates on January 31, the third reduction
since last July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
