<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's 1996/97 Budget Introduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's 1996/97
budget was introduced in National Assembly by Finance Minister
Chris Liebenberg today, attracting mixed responses from political
parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
The new budget saw a modest rise in real expenditure, a
reduction of the deficit and a promise of more efficient tax
collection.
</P>
<P>
Total expenditure is up 10.4 percent at 173.659 billion Rand
(about 47.578 billion US Dollars), revenue rose 13.6 percent to
144.9 billion Rand (about 39.7 billion US Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the deficit dropped to 28.802 billion Rand (about
7.891 billion US Dollars) from previous year's 30.09 billion Rand
(about 8.244 billion US Dollars), representing a drop to 5.1
percent of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) from six percent.
</P>
<P>
The other highlights of the new budget also included no
increase in VAT (value-added-tax), retirement funds to be taxed
at 17 percent of income and interest payments, a 4.6 percent
increase in police budget and five percent cut in defense budget.
</P>
<P>
In his budget speech, Liebenberg said job creation, poverty
relief and crime prevention were identified as priorities for
budget allocations.
</P>
<P>
Liebenberg described his budget as ''excellent'', but his view
was not shared by political parties.
</P>
<P>
The National Party (NP) said the budget deficit was a ''major
cause for concern'' and that the tax burden was too high.
</P>
<P>
NP finance spokesman Theo Alant said the deficit before
borrowing should have been cut to 4.5 percent of GDP through
further reductions to state expenditure.
</P>
<P>
NP's view was echoed by the Democratic Party (DP), whose
finance spokesman Ken Andrew called the ''spend now pay later''
budget ''very disappointing''.
</P>
<P>
Freedom Front finance spokesman Willie Botha said it was
disappointing that Liebenberg sought new sources of income
instead of opting for a reduction in government spending.
</P>
<P>
However, the African National Congress (ANC) and Inkatha
Freedom Party (IFP) welcomed the budget, praising the budget as
one that would create jobs and boost the economy.
</P>
<P>
The ANC said there was ''no cause for alarm'' over the
imposition of the retirement funds tax, and it was pleased that
Liebenberg had resisted the ''short-sighted and insensitive''
advice to raise VAT.
</P>
<P>
The IFP said it believed the budget was ''good and solid'' and
would ''take the country's socio-economic situation forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-13 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portugese Foreign Minister Ends Visit To Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUNDA, March 13 (Xinhua) --Portugese Foreign Minister Jaime
Gama reaffirmed here this evening that Portugal will work for
closer relations between Portugal and Angola.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to newsmen following a meeting with Angolan President
Jose Eduardo dos Santos, the Portuguese foreign minister said
that he is satisfied with the Angolan President's attitude that
he attaches great importance to the development of the relations
between Angola and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
On Angola's relations with European countries, Jaime Gama,
who will end a two-day visit to Angola later today, said that
he will suggest to the European Union for the convention of a
summit conference of the head of states of the European and
African countries to discuss ways to establish new relationship
of partners.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the peace process in Angola, Jaime Gama said
that Portugal will send more troops to the United Nations peace
keeping force in Angola to assume its internatioanl obligation
for the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
During his visit here, the Portugese minister discussed with
the Angolan leaders bilateral relations, Angola's peace process
and foreign debts. 
