<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 13 (Xinhua) -- United Nations officials today
expressed concern over incidents of terrorising and looting of
Serb homes in Ilidza by gangs from Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
The previously Serb controlled Ilidza has been handed over to
the Bosnian Federation since Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"several Serbs who wanted to stay in Ilidza are now informing
the U.N. they have no choice but to leave," said Alexander Ivanko,
spokesman for the U.N. police force.
</P>
<P>
"This is another blow to the multi-ethnicity of Sarajevo,"
Ivanko said, "It's really a shame that some people who have come
Sarajevo to Ilidza are behaving in the same way as some Serbs
before leaving the area, they are intimidating and harassing
people."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman or the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, Kris
Janowski, said that he saw during a tour of Ilidza that "hundreds
of people entering other people's apartments."
</P>
<P>
"One resident was threatened with a hand grenade, a second with
a pistol, while another with an explosive device," he said, adding
that many vehicles without license plates are moving through
Ilidza.
</P>
<P>
Janowski said that federal police has reacted in some cases,
but that there are too few of them to prevent all criminal acts.
</P>
