<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Calls for Comprehensive, Lasting Peace in Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government today
stressed that the achievement of a comprehensive, just and
lasting peace in the region will lead to an end of the violence
and terror.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers asserted that Lebanon considers that
a correct framework for dealing with the problem of terrorism and
violence is to make efforts to find a comprehensive, just and
lasting settlement to the Middle East issue.
</P>
<P>
Hours after an international anti-terrorism summit ended in the
Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el Sheikh, Lebanese President
Elias Hrawi convened a regular session of the Council of Ministers
in the Presidential Palace here this evening.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, President Hrawi called for an
implementation of U.N. Security Council resolution 425, which
demands an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon,
according to a statement read out by Information Minister Farid
Mkari at the end of the cabinet session.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi disclosed that in a conference of Arab foreign ministers
in Cairo Thursday, Lebanon will announce its own position on the
Israeli aggressions (in South Lebanon) and on what is happening
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz left here earlier today
for Cairo to attend the 105th conference of the Arab League
Council, which was postponed for one day due to today's
anti-terrorism summit held in Sharm el Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the Council of Ministers expressed
its support for a decision taken by the president to boycott the
summit at Sharm el Sheikh. The council stressed that Lebanon holds
that there is a distinction between terrorism and the legitimate
right of defending the land.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria were the only countries which had been
invited but were absent in the Sharm el Sheikh summit.
</P>
<P>
Clarifying Lebanon's decision to boycott the summit conference,
the statement said that this summit dealt with the subject of
terrorism, at a time when the basic problem in the Middle East is
political, for which a demanded solution has not yet been achieved.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the statement added, came responding to the
recent violence in Israel, while Lebanon suffers daily aggressions
without anyone calling for a stop of the terrorism and violent
operations against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon has always called, and is still calling for an
distinction between terrorism and the right of the legitimate
resistance which is guaranteed and practiced by a number of
countries," the statement stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
