<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Syrian FMs Discuss Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa met with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al Sharaa on the
ongoing Middle East peace process and the outcome of an
international anti-terrorism summit held in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place on the sideline of the 105th session of
the Arab League Council, which opened here earlier today with the
participation of the foreign ministers of its 22 member states.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and Sharaa, in particular, assessed the situation in the
region following the anti-terrorism summit, or summit of
peacemakers, held Wednesday in the Egyptian Red Sea resort city of
Sharm el Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, Moussa emphasized the need to maintain
the momentum of the peace process on all tracks, saying that this
was a demand of all Arabs.
</P>
<P>
He said all acts of violence must be condemned, no matter they
take place in Israel or against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question about Syria's absence from the summit of
peacemakers,
Moussa said that Syria's failure to attend was "a fact that
we regret."
</P>
<P>
"Yet we have represented the Syrian side and the whole Arab
side in the summit, because the Arab interests are one and the
same, namely, consolidation of the peace process, containing
violence and continuation of the process towards its ultimate goal
on the basis of the land-for-peace principle," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the restoration of occupied Arab territories
and the Palestinian people's legitimate rights.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister pointed out that there were some
differences between the two countries with regard to the
evaluation of the summit, but such differences would not affect
the policy of coordination between Egypt and Syria in the best
interests of peace, the Arab stance and the future of the region.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Sharaa expressed his country's great confidence in
Egypt, saying that the Syrian and Egyptian peoples entertained
historic, fraternal and deep-rooted ties, which could not be
shaken by external events.
</P>
<P>
Sharaa pointed out that the political leadership in Syria had
taken a decision not to participate in the Sharm el Sheikh summit,
after a thorough examination of all possible eventualities and
realities.
</P>
<P>
The leadership reached the conclusion of non-participation, as
Syria was still suffering from Israeli occupation despite the
lapse of four years since the inception of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the conviction that the closing statement of the
peacemakers summit serves the Israeli side more than it does the
Arab side.
</P>
<P>
He said that the peacemakers summit left no room for
distinction between terrorism and what is not terrorism, namely,
the resistance of occupation.
</P>
<P>
Sharaa emphasized Syria's commitment to the peace process,
saying that no one could cast any doubt about Syria's adherence to
the peace option. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
