<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 71 People Injured during Riots in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 71 people were
injured and eight others were arrested here today following
clashes outside the Cyprus Archbishop's palace between the
anti-riot police and supporters of a clergyman.
</P>
<P>
The clergyman, Archimandrite Pangratios Meraklis, was facing
charges of "improper moral conduct" before the Holy Synod, the
island's supreme church body.
</P>
<P>
According to a police spokesman, two policemen and three
demonstrators were hospitalized for further treatment. Eight more
policemen and 58 demonstrators who were taken to hospital, mostly
suffering from breathing problems caused by the tear gas, were
later released.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, some 2,000 demonstrators, who want Meraklis, 39,
to become Bishop of Morphou area, partly occupied by the Turkish
troops since 1974, tried to break police barriers around the
Archbishop's palace in the walled city of Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The clash took place when some 410 policemen, including 140
anti-riot police members, used tear gas and other means to
disperse the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Glafcos Xenos pointed out that the police
were left with no other choice to restore law and order other
than taking anti-riot measures.
</P>
<P>
Deputy police chief Panikos Hadjiloizou also confirmed that
Cyprus police had information that some extremist groups of
supporters were planning to use explosives and that they received
an anonymous call saying that the life of Archbishop Chrysostomos
was in danger.
</P>
<P>
The Archbishop has stated that Meraklis was "unfit" for the
post of the Bishop of Morphou, accusing him of "moral
misconduct".
</P>
<P>
A Holy Synod press release said three prosecution witnesses
failed to appear before the body today because they had been
threatened by Meraklis' supporters. A fourth witness, a
clergyman, testified against Meraklis.
</P>
<P>
The press release also said the Meraklis appeared before the
Holy Synod and declared that he was not guilty of charges of
"improper moral conduct."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, government spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides appealed
for calm and the restoration of law and order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
