<DOCNO> XIE19960314.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-03-14 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emergency Rule Extended in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The emergency rule in 10
provinces in southeastern Turkey will be extended, probably for
the last time, for another period of four months as of March 19
following a lengthy debate in the parliament today.
</P>
<P>
This was the 26th time in 18 years that Turkish legislature
extended the emergency rule, which gives sweeping power to local
authorities in fighting with the separatist Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The government's extension draft was passed by a vote of 227 to
 179 with 51 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Ulku Guney said that the extension of the
emergency rule would help boost the morale of the security forces
in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
He assured that the government in next four months would work
on alternative law drafts, such as ID checks, possession of arms
and administration of villages and provinces, and bring it to the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Some deputies who took the floor during today's session
pointed out that the Kurdish problem cannot be solved by simply
killing the separatists and that a democratic approach with
political and economic solutions should be introduced.
</P>
<P>
"You cannot fight mosquitos by killing them one by one,"
said one deputy. "You have to drain the swamp".
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that more than 20,000 people have died,
countless wounded in the fighting between the Kurdish rebels and
government forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
